ok, so i'm finally going to write a review for this place.this is my favorite bar. i hang out here all the time. it has something for everyone.where to start?1. kick ass <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. 5-8 is far better than the early afternoon that i see a lot of other places offer. 5 dollar beer is good until you see just what they have on tap and are offering for 5 bucks, then it becomes insanely good. the beer selection used to be good but limited but since the addition of a bunch of new taps it's now just plain good.2. the cocktail program is fantastic, and while neat can also offer a top notch cocktail experience in glendale the famous offers one that's comparable but with a much more approachable atmosphere that the more casual patron can enjoy.3. the people that work there are all awesome. nice, knowledgeable and good for a laugh if you stop to talk to them but even more importantly they're all good at their jobs, they know what they're talking about and they know how to take care of you if you let them.4. the location. it's right across the street from the americana and it's surrounded by awesome parking options. let's be real here folks this is an awesome bar that actually has good parking that you don't need to pay for. if you're an la native you know how valuable that is.i personally prefer to park in the lot next to the library and bevmo on harvard. it's metered but only costs 50 cents an <span class="highlighted">hour</span> until 10 o'clock, after 10 it's free until the morning. there is also the marketplace garage about a block away on maryland which is free for 90 minutes if you're just trying to grab a quick <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. the americana also has a big garage but you'll only get an <span class="highlighted">hour</span> of free parking there without a validation of some kind.5. it's just plain fun. i've seen it packed and i've seen it on slow nights, it's fun either way. when it's quiet you can rely on the fact that it's comfortable and spacious while always having some &nbsp;interesting movie on the projectors. they have live music most tuesdays when i'm there and even on nights when they don't the grand piano in the back is open to anyone that can play.this is your neighborhood dive bar without the dive. i hang out all over la but i always come back to the famous. it's the kind of bar that i wish they had in glendale a long time ago.
i am so <span class="highlighted">happy</span> a place like this that has opened up in glendale. lord knows glendale needs something new and exciting! i never think to hang out or go bar hoping in glendale...ever! well now thing's have changed :)the bar itself is big and spacious...it would be hard for anyone to feel claustrophobic. the decor is great: perfectly dim lights, with brown-themed simple, classy furniture &amp; the awesome touch of exposing the original brick wall of the building makes this place very cozy.i have to come here for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>; drink prices are a bit pricey ($12) but they are very stiff &amp; the lovely mixology-trained bartenders will take their time to ensure your drink is just right. i had one of the bartenders dump the whole thing out cuz he didn't feel it tasted like it should.we met the owners who were super nice, so i wish them all the best &amp; hope this place gains steam so it can be a success!
a trip here just before any new year's craziness resulted in a chill visit to this whiskey bar. &nbsp;dark woods, cushion-y bar stools for my big butt, and plenty of space to lounge out.fine cocktails and new inventions, i kicked off my visit with the recommended live young die fast cocktail -- a spicy kick-in-your-mouth drink garnished with basil and boozed with gin. &nbsp;i'm no gin drinker, but the drink itself was pretty hot. &nbsp;i've never ventured into savory or spicy drinks, so this was a pretty neat intro.i followed this up the french (bubbly cognac concoction), russian std mule (which was fine - but average) and the namesake famous cocktail, which i enjoyed.they have a <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> i could meet, a few beers on the menu, and the place is new enough that they are currently relying on word-of-mouth advertising.i don't know yet what sort of regular crowd is popping up here, but there were some annoyingly boisterous drunk people on my visit, but they didn't last long.good place for a drink, whether by yourself or a few others.i enjoyed my bartender, who was very meticulous about serving me up good looking beverages that are made with care.
i went during <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> and it was awesome. was not crowded at all. the bartenders were seriously cool dudes. when i open a tab, i usually have to repeat my last name everything i get a drink. they actually remembered me. i got pretty much beers the whole night but i did order one of their cocktails named &quot;the captain.&quot;i think the captain tasted horrible, but i do appreciate that it took some skill and time to make it. lighting up an orange peel? smashing sugar? using aromatics? this drink took a few minutes to make and that honestly, was pretty cool. at one point i was like &quot; oh cool, he's done.&quot; nope. let me mesmerize you with more witchcraft.  it was a nice setting where me and my friends could enjoy a drink and there was a movie playing on the projector. the restrooms had pictures of pinups instead of the usual ....nothing? &nbsp;dim lighting but that's whatever, we were there when the sun was still out. &nbsp;a few times the music that was playing felt really downer, but one of the guys changed it right away to keep the mood up.
stopped in for the first time on tuesday, then returned again the very next night... their old fashioned skills are that good. &nbsp;on tuesday, i was solo, and completely sober upon arrival. &nbsp;i missed their <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> ($2.00 off most drinks) by 2 minutes, but did not care once i tasted my drink. &nbsp;david, as well as every other bartender in the place, makes old fashioneds just the way i like them. &nbsp;you will not find any cherries in your old fashioneds here. &nbsp;picture seven grand as opposed to cpk. &nbsp;i only had time for one drink tuesday, but on wednesday, a bit more. &nbsp;i returned for a friend's bday with a party of 6. &nbsp;ironically, none of them had even ever heard of &quot;the famous&quot; before. &nbsp;if the famous isn't by now, it definitely should be. &nbsp;everyone in my party agreed that the drinks and vibe there were excellent. in just two quick visits, they have already jumped into my top 3 places to grab a drink in la. &nbsp;as bill m. so eloquently put it in his review - the journeyman ravenswood rye whiskey is perfect for an old fashioned. &nbsp;i will be sure to get &quot;stache's&quot; name when i return, and give him the proper acknowledgment for his perfect drink suggestion. &nbsp;and at only $13.00 a pop ($11.00 if ordered on its own, $2.00 to make it an old fashioned), i see no reason to ever drive down the wallet busting whistlepig highway again.overall i went with 4 stars because i still have to try them out on a busier night, when the food trucks i've heard about make their appearance. &nbsp;after i have tried all that the famous has to offer, i will update my review/rating accordingly. &nbsp;until then, i highly recommend the famous for all non-cpk style old fashioned fans.
been waiting for a place like this to open in this area for a very long time. &nbsp;i hope and pray that they stick around. &nbsp;i like the ambiance and they do make a great drink and have great <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> specials. &nbsp;all this will stay. &nbsp;a few things they should improve on if they want to stick around. &nbsp;get the food menu straight. &nbsp;i know they are just starting out but not having truffle fries or getting 3 instead of 4 pieces on an app all lead to confusion and a subpar experience. &nbsp;just keep the menu simple and get it right and make sure the food is tasty. &nbsp; if you are going to have a speak easy type of a bar, it would be great if the bartenders looked a little more stylish. &nbsp;class it up a little. &nbsp;maybe have 1 drink special all night so the beer drinking customers might actually give the drinks are try and not feel bad instead of spending $12. &nbsp;over all i love it, but i worry this bar might not be in the right neighborhood. i will tell everyone i know to go there but i hope they keep up their end but providing excellent service as well. &nbsp;good luck famous...i am rooting for you!!
