dude...dude.i've been living .3 miles from this place since it opened, and i never knew this culinary marvel existed. and you know what? i'm kinda pissed that yelp didn't give this place as high a rating, making me think i could skip just another wannabe silverlake hipster &quot;tavern&quot; in the atwater area. also i'm moving next week and won't be able to savor this delectable blessing again (well i'm not even moving that far, but, the 101...you know).i got the bbq chicken nachos. &quot;nachos aren't really a meal,&quot; you might say. but this was a revelation: chunks of tender, glazed bbq chicken punctuate the mount of chips, which are expertly layered with cheese and beans--no naked chips at the bottom of the pile! i shamefully admit that i polished off the whole plate. the hubs ordered the brisket burrito, of which i was able to steal one luscious bite before he wolfed it down. i knew bbq + mexican would be a great combo, but...whoa. they also have a pretty impressive beer list (if you're into that sort of thing) and some good <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> specials. definitely going back the next time i'm in the area.
my most fantastic local find this year! it's so good i almost don't want to blow it up on here as i don't want yall taking overbut - damn it's amazing they deserve this review.my new favorite thing - pickled jalapeno rings with pulled pork and slaw! killer! i literally wanted to go back the next day just for those! i restrained myself just writing about it makes me want it now!!!super clever hybrid of bbq and mexican - if they only had sushi it would be my perfect place - but they rally don't need it when they have &quot;crazy corn&quot; - the best grilled corn with savory sauces ever - and i make this dish a lot for parties and my friends and these guys make mine look like baby food! seriously check this place out - cool out door patio with water for dogs. decent <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> friendly staff and good prices!i can't write any more i will only want to eat it now and it's late! :(check this little atwater hole in the wall out - it's amazing!
after the six month settling-in period, time to visit avt - many, many craft brews (1/2 on-tap) and a decent collection of custom cocktails. &nbsp;daily drink specials are great and in the $2-5 range, even if you're not around <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. the service is bar-style - go up to the bar/counter, order and tag your table with a # sign (preferably gathering your utensils, napkins and water cups on the way back.)2 tv's on sports; the touchscreen jukebox (touchtunes), is also a photobooth ($0.50/play or $3 for a photo) and controllable by iphone/android app, if you wish. &nbsp;it's an eclectic mix of music that isn't exactly going to turn the place into either a rave party nor a country line-dancing stomp, but it's curious enough of a variety to find new music to listen while you embibe and injest.the food menu is what caught me off-guard. what looks like perhaps a tex-cali-mex street taco/burrito/tostada assembly, has a distinct number of vegan-friendly options that are worth exploring (hence how the avocado &quot;fries&quot; showed up - they're actually more like avocado tempura slices.) &nbsp;the &quot;buffalo&quot; roasted cauliflower &quot;wings&quot; was quite fun - roast large clusters of cauliflower, and toss them in wing sauce. a bbq diced chicken tostada salad was quite flavorful - everything is mildly spiced, so you'll have to hot sauce things to kick it up a notch. jalapeno rings are sort of like mildly spicy versions of fried pickle chips. crazy cob is a good version of good old el elote loco, though priced double of your typical shopping cart vendor on olympic bl. the fish burrito was totally well-balanced, and similar to a wahoo-style without any rice.had our dog along, who was welcome on the sheltered and heated patio (not that we've needed that this year in the 80's in january.) &nbsp;runners gathered the empty plates quickly, but you'll have to visit the bar again for any additions or drinks to be added to your tab.fun, chill-out and relax place, sit at the bar if you want to catch a game, and a nice beery addition to the atwater central proprietors.
the-moose-den-glendale-2
<span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> review.<span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> is daily from 3-7pm and all day monday.this bar has been open since january 2015 and is owned by the same person as 'the famous', which is directly next door.the space is a very casual, retro design. upon entering from the street, you actually walk down into the bar. it's a basement restaurant, pub and game room. bartenders were quite chatty, laid back, and friendly. they have all draft beers,wine, and house cocktails for $1 off regular prices. they also serve a cheeseburger, fries with miller's lite or coors for $14. there are a variety draft beers on tap, which rotate, and a nice variety of ales. unfortunately, they do not serve barleywine, at least as of yet.this is a great addition to glendale, which is not really known for its cool pub scene.tip - the americana is located across the streetparking - free 90 minute garage parking on maryland ave or limited free street parking a 2-3 blocks away
