why did i never eat here until now? &nbsp;that is because my hubby had told me that he didn't like the place. &nbsp;because he ate here 10 years ago, &nbsp;when he was poor and could only afford the <span class="highlighted">happy-hour</span> fried appetizers.i should have know better than to listen to him!! great place, great comfortable atmosphere &amp; vibe. &nbsp;the food did take about 20 minutes to come out, but damn - it was worth the wait. &nbsp;i had the:prime top sirloin steak $17.95center-cut sirloin steak, grilled to order and topped with a bleu cheese peppercorn saucei ate everything off of my plate, including the garnish. &nbsp;the crowd can be a little older (okay, a lot older depending on what time you are there), but on a friday night there was a buzzing crowd at the long bar and a great vibe overall. &nbsp; live jazz everynight (during happyhour, and from 9pm to 1am).
jax gets a 5 for the old timey &quot;ratpack&quot;- like atmosphere, a 3.5 for the service and a 4 for the beer selection and a 3 for the food. food is oh kay. you're probably better to stick w/ appetizers than anything else. the food is oh kay but not anything special and it's not super expensive, but you can get much better for that price elsewhere. even the free wings they put out during <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> are pretty bad. the front part of the restaurant has a nice vibe to it. it definitely feels like a place your grandparents may have gone to 50 or 60 years ago, but in a &quot;hip&quot; sorta way. there are a couple of annoying waiters that have been there a long time and some non-annoying servers as well. the back part of the restaurant is huge! music at nite is oh kay. nothing great, usually a bit cheezy. i guess it's a nice touch? some may like it more than others. the cheese factor of their musicians isn't high on my list. so really, this place is more of a 3.5 but i'll give it a 4 instead of a 3, b/c it's better than 3 if you're just having a beer or 2 and maybe an app.
had a rough day yesterday and today, so what better solution than to go to <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> at the local bar. something about the holidays that makes me sad, which is because i really can't be with the one i love...i just try to get a hold of my guy that i love, but i can sense a lot of people are preventing that....so, i ordered a mystery beer for $2. i hate beer, but figured that should cheer me up. then, like the other reviewer tiffany, i felt persuaded to order the sauteed barcelona shrimp, which sounded deliciously fancy, but wasn't to my liking. i didn't have the heart to send it back since the bartender staff &nbsp;(first the guy, then the girl) were very attentive, gracious, and always made sure i was doing ok and <span class="highlighted">happy</span>. next time, i have to remember being adventurous may not be the best thing to do....but hey, i did have leftovers, which i appreciate due to the large portion. and coming from an appetizer, you get your $15 worth. however, next time i will be sure to order a fish or pasta dish, something more filling. with this dish, you do have to mix it with the bread to really appreciate the dish.i loved the piano playing not only christmas songs, but also some barry manilow songs and other romance songs. it made me more sad a little, but i had my readings with me to help distract me.....next time i have to try the pumpkin martini as well as sit by the piano to chase my blues.......and hopefully with someone i love.....i wonder if he thinks of me and ever wants to see me the way i want to see him.....
wow this place is place is filled with a bunch of old timers! middle aged - geezer status! don't get me wrong i have nothing against senior citizens, but i'm just not used to enjoying a drink at the bar with the geriatrics. we were the youngest ones inside that entire joint. &nbsp;a friend and i decided to stop in for the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> and live jazz, but it was pretty lame when we found out that the band wasn't getting on until 9. by that time we headed out to our second destination so we didn't get the full experience. ehh maybe next time. &nbsp;at least we did catch the exciting laker game that went down to the wire. it was hilarious hearing loud mouths at the bar yelling &quot;shiiiiiiiiiit!!!&quot; when gasol missed a free throw to tie the game up during crunch time. go heat! &nbsp;anyways... the people here are friendly, drinks are a bit pricey.. a stiff jack n' coke ran up to 8 bucks, and although i did not try the food, some of their dish's looked really good.
this place is the shizzy. &nbsp;it deserves every last star up here because it rocks. &nbsp;i know that most of my <span class="highlighted">happiness</span> over it is due to the novelty. &nbsp;we don't have places this cool where i live. &nbsp;glendale is a good 40 minutes to an <span class="highlighted">hour</span> away. &nbsp;i was in the area performing for some old lady who tricked me into dancing at her birthday for free. &nbsp;after which, my bf proclaimed we needed to celebrate my 'retirement' from performing for free. &nbsp;(he's not going to let me fall for that again!)i started with an outstanding lemon drop. &nbsp;tart and strong. &nbsp;i should have had something stiffer, but i hadn't eaten since morning. &nbsp;i had a bite of the warm, fresh sourdough and it was delicious! &nbsp;but i mean, when is fresh warm sourdough not delicious?thankfully, yelpers had steered me in good directions when it comes to food. &nbsp;my baby had the cornflake tenders. &nbsp;i think he felt it was some of the best white meat chicken he's had. &nbsp;he usually steers clear of white meat and likes the moisture that dark meat chicken brings. &nbsp;i had the cedar plank salmon. &nbsp;hands down the best salmon i've had in a while. &nbsp;it had a loose crust that i want to say was panko, the crust was buttery, light and perfect with the mustard rub. &nbsp;it came with delicious quick pickle, i usually don't like quick pickle. &nbsp;most of the time it's too sweet or just tasted like soggy cucumber, but this was a perfect balance. &nbsp;the carrots were also perfectly cooked and not too buttery. &nbsp;however, the zucchini was the vegetable standout. &nbsp;i don't know how they managed to make it so good, but it was so good. &nbsp;after they cooked it, they tossed it in some sort of warm relish with tomato, red onion and green onion. &nbsp;the flavor was amazing. &nbsp;i'll eat zucchini in any form, it's one of my favorite forms of produce, but this was truly amazing.on a sad note, the second lemon drop i had was way sweeter and subpar compared to the first one. &nbsp;but hey, i'm willing to forgive. &nbsp;when there is jazz fiddle and trumpet going on with food this bomb... i can take everything else in stride.
