the friends and i had dinner at hyperion public on a friday night. the good thing is that we all had never been here before so everyone's palate was a nice clean slate. the bad thing...my palate was restrained. as a practicing catholic i couldn't eat meat on fridays during lent, which means no steaks and no fried chicken for this girl.the dining area was relatively small. luckily we had reservations at 8pm so there was one long rectangular table in the middle for the 8 of us.brussels gratin - very tasty and crisp. can never go wrong with brussels sprouts.roasted mushroom quinoa salad - average-sized salad but is it worth $11? love arugula and cucumbers but the oregano vinaigrette made the dish taste rather sour.sea dog raspberry wheat ale - i really liked this beer. i don't necessarily drink beer but i do love a good wheat ale every once in awhile.our table also ordered the oh my goodness dip and pan-seared crab cakes. everyone raved about the appetizers but as far as the entrees--mediocre. the crispy fried buttermilk chicken was enjoyed by the bf but average for the others. the truffle mac n cheese was decent and very cheesy but was also very small for $11. our conclusion: hyperion public ideal for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> and after-dinner drinks but not for a great meal. grab a bite to eat elsewhere.
i was really looking forward to trying this place. i passed it once and was drawn in by the big window and twinkling lights. when i found out their <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> runs until 7, i decided to finally check it out and made ressies on opentable.when we arrived, there were 'reserved' signs everywhere, including a row of empty tables. however, they decided to seat us at a small, cramped table between a family with small children and another party. uh...no. luckily, our server saw our hesitation and offered to move us without our asking. we finally sit down and i notice we weren't given a hh menu, so i had to ask for that after our first drink order was put in. hh deals range from $4 glasses of house wine, $2 off cocktails and lots of food items. i ordered the crab cakes, which were a bit salty. for dinner, i was debating between the winter kale salad or the vegan pot pie. i have to give them props for catering to all diets. i ended up with the salad, which was filling and good. but again, on the salty side. my bf has a thing for mac and cheese, so he ordered their special with bbq pulled pork. now if there's one requirement for good mac and cheese, it would be that it's....wait for it....cheesy. no brainer, right? well unfortunately, cheesy this was not. and the pork had bones in it. the drinks weren't much better. the dirty martini came out tasting like it was half filled with vermouth. good lord. i really, really wanted to like this place. but as we left, i told my bf my favorite thing about this place was the music. fail.
did we get a substitute chef? &nbsp;because the meal we had was an insult to actual gastropubs like village idiot. i'll give hyperion pub points for ambiance - it looks like a proper gastropub. but after eating the food and seeing the bill, i wasn't surprised the place was mostly empty at 8 pm. &nbsp;we had: truffle mac &amp; cheese - blessedly light on the truffle oil (maybe even too light - there was truffle oil in it?), the mac &amp; cheese was watery and thin... not at all creamy. more like a lightly cheesy rotini soup. the hyperion burger - meh. the beef was fine, but the bun was stale; the tomato was one of those watery, tasteless tomatoes you got in the school lunchroom and the bacon had a weird burnt-plastic taste. i should've opted for the fries... instead i got the healthy side salad, which turned out to be soggy greens drenched in dressing. the halibut - our mistake for ordering something healthy. the tiny bit of fish was overcooked and rubbery; the plate was swimming in tasteless lentils, and i think the julienned vegetables were actually raw, which made no sense.the beer and wine selection was good, but $11 for a tiny glass of joel gott cabernet is ridiculous - the whole bottle doesn't cost a lot more than that. our bill came to $90 for two people. i don't actually mind paying $90 for a good meal, but this one felt like i went to a bad dinner party and had my wallet stolen. my advice: go for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> and skip the food.
