we know all there is to know about scottish culture, correct? let's check our list: scottish terriers, plaid kilts, haunted castles, mary queen of scots, and bag pipes. that's it, right? alright, so there is way more to know about scotland than the average american can attest to, but i have a great way to get started on your scottish study lesson: tam o' shanter in los feliz.owned by lowry's, tam o' shanter is a &nbsp;boarding pass to a scottish restaurant/bar without the hefty-costing airline ticket. architecturally, you will be swept into a the world of a scottish cottage with stained-glass windows, antique ovens, and a dining room which looks straight out of a king's eating hall. adding to the allure are the numerous tales of ghost hauntings and paranormal experiences (ask the employees about these). don't worry though, they only come out after-<span class="highlighted">hours</span>! ascestically, tan o' shanter is an ideal, unique dining experience.looking for a bit more of a scottish pub environment? the bar (featuring sports-broadcasting tvs) while still adding elements of class and scottish history; will fill your void. <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> is from 4-7pm and with such beers at local golden road hef on tap ($5 <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> price-- normally $7), your alcohol taste buds will be <span class="highlighted">happy</span>. although, <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> only involves standard drinks like beer and simple cocktails like vodka/cranberry so don't expect an extensive <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> drink menu (appetizers are $3 off). one of the exciting elements at tam o' shanter are the carolers whom stride through the restaurant during 4-9pm in the month of december. dressed in dickens-esque costume, you can't possibly not get into the christmas spirit. they personally go to specific tables and perform a personal concert. singing &quot;o holy night&quot; for my boyfriend and i, they certainly brought us warm cheer.employees at tam's are at the top of their game. polite, quick, and always in a relaxed mood (despite the chaotic restaurant); you shouldn't have much of an issue with service. the manager even remembered us from the yelp event held here which was very impressive.so whether you want a taste of scotland or merely an experience which differs from the usual la offerings, head to tam o' shanter. it is something worth seeing.
this was walt disney's favorite restaurant, and it has been around since the road was dirt, and it was considered out in the country. it was family owned for decades, then owned by the van de kamps, and now owned by lawrey's. there is a little historic display in the lobby to explain.but whereas lawrey's is an english prime rib place, tam o'shanter's is a scottish restaurant. the walls are covered with scottish coats of arms (very fun to look up your scottish family name if you have one and see your crest), and there are special scottish nights like robbie burn's birthday on january 25th each year, where they sing songs, do dances, and serve haggis. reservations must be made for this at least a month in advance.the main dish to get here is prime rib. the only downside is that they carve it in the kitchen (the actual lawrey's restaurants have old fashioned carts, which i think is much better). but that aside, the prime rib is excellent. there is also a bar that has an eating area that serves inexpensive prime rib sandwiches for lunch.as far as sides go i love the creamed spinach, but the creamed corn is also amazing. get both. tam's has a good selection of scotches and ales, and also a great <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, but only for drinks (no food on <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>).this is a favorite place of mine.
