tam o'shanter is the friendly, approachable cousin to the lawry chain of prime beef restaurants (the family member one likes best). &nbsp;tucked in the corner of los feliz since the 20's, tam is a cross between disney and scottish kitsch and is a highland castle sized space that remains intimate, friendly and authentic.i've been coming here for years and never tire of the charm of its tudor rooms lined with tartan plaids, prints of highland scenes, and ambient fireplaces. the attentive wait-staff is appropriately garbed in themed-attire. &nbsp;the food is consistently delicious. &nbsp;i don't always go for the prime rib with yorkshire pudding since their other menu items are equally well-prepared. i often begin my meal with a well concocted manhattan cocktail (they have a separate scotch-whiskey listing) and always enjoy the house chardonnay--it is buttery and oakey to perfection. &nbsp;tam has a nice <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> and often features talented groups performing lively, foot-stomping celtic music. &nbsp;there is a bar carving station serving lighter and cheaper fare to go with your ale.check out tam o'shanter for any family celebration, romantic evening, or satisfying evening out eating well!
so i've lived in the silverlake/los feliz/glendale area for nearly my entire life and somehow missed one of the most special, unique gems of the neighborhood because i don't like prime rib. i suppose i figured it was an overpriced and geriatric-laden-crotchety-old-man place. this past holiday season, a friend suggested we all met up at the ale &amp; sandwich bar after work. i was hungry and wanted a beer so we joined. omg! it is soooooooo cute inside! it was a few weeks before christmas and the whole place was decked out. fireplace going, carolers walking around taking requests, those tiny little alcoves with the wingback chairs and pedestal tables. i was in love. and then i got a hand-carved brisket sandwich on a brioche bun and it was total and utter heaven. they have a little carving station and a sides station with awesome potato salad. i don't really like their coleslaw a whole lot though. i would recommend the tam for a cold, rainy evening, <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> any day, or for whenever you want to rip into a super-moist, meatstravaganza of a sandwich.
i have seen this place while on route to the los feliz costco, and have been wanting to try it. &nbsp;well, a date night with hubby provided the perfect opportunity! &nbsp;as has been said in other reviews, tam o'shanter is brought to you by the lawry's prime rib folks, but has a much more laid-back vibe and a better menu. &nbsp;i thoroughly enjoyed my toad in the hole, which is yummy filet mignon stew; but couldn't even do it justice for having gorged in the scotch rarebit (fondue). &nbsp;the drinks are very well-done as well, and service is absolutely impeccable. &nbsp;our waitress, melinda, was so attentive and helpful with suggestions; the gentleman bussing our table was on his game and so so polite. &nbsp;in addition, the manager on duty came by our table to make sure that everything was to our liking. &nbsp;as we were leaving, we noticed a band playing live music; so i can totally see coming here for a laid-back <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. &nbsp;for those who are la history buffs like me, walt disney, john wayne, and mary pickford used to frequent this place. &nbsp;you can see the influence of it today at disneyland. &nbsp;i am so very glad that hubby and i had a chance to share this most special dining opportunity.
having lived in the los feliz area almost my entire life, i have surprisingly never set afoot in this joint. we always went to lawry's on la cienega but never thought about tam o'shanter which is only five minutes away; both are under the same company. when dinela came around, the fellas and i decided to give it a shot. a reservation is highly recommended especially if you have a party of 12 like we did.sharon, our lovely waitress was on point. our table can be somewhat of a rough crowd but she handled the situation flawlessly. using the dinela as an excuse to get together and eat here didn't go too far. out of the twelve guys, only two ordered off that set menu. the rest came of us came to the conclusion that the 6 oz prime rib cut and small lobster tail from that prefix deal wasn't going to cut it.many of the items in the menu are very similar to what you would see in lawry's menu. the californian cut, the english cut, instead of the lawry's cut you have the prince charlie cut, of course the infamous lawry's signature creamed corn and spinach (there's chopped bacon in it!) is available. the difference is that tam offers a lot more variety than its counterpart. everything from soups, salads, to different appetizers, steak, and an array of seafood options. also, don't expect the medallion bling bling'd out chef to come out and carve your meat in the carnivore wagon like at lawry's.we started with the golden fried calamari ($12) which i thought was pretty good but for that price, they could've given us more. i barely had two pieces and the rest was conquered in a second by my buddies. we also had the mac &amp; cheese ($7), another simple side dish that's on the pricier scale probably due to the fact that they used smoked gouda and wisconsin cheddar. it was thick yet still runny, but nothing super special.i settled with the tam o'shanter cut ($31), medium, which i came to the conclusion that i should have went with medium rare instead. don't be afraid to ask for extra au jus sauce because the meat soaks it all up in the plate. instead of the mash and gravy, i asked for creamed corn and spinach which are pretty much a guaranteed hit. if you like the prime rib at lawry's, then you will have no issues having it here because i wasn't able to tell if there was a difference between the two. the yorkshire pudding is different though; it has a little more volume and is a bit harder. that extra au jus will help soften it up.tam o'shanter is like a toned down version of lawry's. maybe not as fancy, but the food is of the same caliber. the price might be slightly cheaper and there are more options on the menu. the whole environment is more relaxed but i still wouldn't show up in shorts, sandals, and a grungy tee. got to love the whole scottish theme as well as the staff's classic uniforms.when you first enter the establishment, there's a bar on the left which you can also find a sandwich bar next to it. think of higher end bar food, sandwiches and what not. i believe there's <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> and they did have sunday night football on the flat screens.and to reiterate on the service because it was impeccable. our waters never ran dry including some of the ice teas on the table. because it was our first time dining there (we did celebrate two late bdays as well), sharon gave us complimentary english trifle to share. kudos to the staff especially to her. my pal nat y. would like to personally commend the hostess chloe for not only being nice but helping us snap a group pic.by the end of the meal, we were all stuffed and very satisfied. i know now that i don't need to travel all the way to beverly hills for some tasty prime rib or for some of that tasty creamed corn. tam o'shanter deserves more recognition than just being a distant cousin of lawry's. don't forget, you can also use your lawry's vip membership here to rack up points!valet parking is available but there was plenty of free street parking if you want to save some cash.
the bf and i were actually on our way to little tokyo but traffic was insane! we had been battling traffic for close to an <span class="highlighted">hour</span>, our starting point was burbank and we only made it atwater village by way of side streets in that time. my stomach and temper were desperately shouting at me and the bf was on pins and needles... he knows how i get... lol.anyway, i recently went to tam o'shanter for the first time during a yelp elite event and remembered how impressed i was. it was my duty as navigator to call it quits on our initial destination and settle on tam o'shanter as our next stop - the bf happily agreed.the place was pretty busy, no surprise as a lot of patrons were getting together for the holidays and it was a friday night! luckily we snagged a booth in the bar, score!carlisle was our server and provided excellent service. he did forget to bring out a side of gravy but it's okay, poor guy was slammed and we could tell he was doing his best.we ordered:french onion soup, big enough to share between 2 people. it had a lot of flavor and was served at a nice hot temperature.tam o'shanter cut med-rare, we shared this between the two of us and each got a lobster tail. it was more than enough food!! i got mine with cream corn and spinach while the bf got cream corn and mashed potatoes. next time, i'll skip the spinach and get double corn or a side of potatoes. the yorkshire pudding was good too, especially when you sop it up with gravy!!we ended our meal with an order of chocolate souffle. good god, this thing was massive!! it came with a side of cream and it was really rich.. we were only able to take a few bites before raising the white flag.it's definitely a place to indulge while feeling comfortable and cozy, you could probably fall asleep for a few minutes before realizing it! the decor and ambiance of the place is really amazing, a nice cherry on top for the history buffs as well as they have a lot of memorabilia of the establishment circa 1920's i believe. i know the bf took a good ten minutes to peruse all the articles and photos.i'm <span class="highlighted">happy</span> to have discovered tam o'shanter after so many years of seeing it and wondering about it. i especially like the fact that i can come here rather than make the drive down to beverly hills. to be honest, i prefer this venue itself over lawry's.... there's just something nostalgic about it that gives you that warm fuzzy feeling. great spot, especially during the holidays!
