valar morghulis means all men must die in high valyrian. but you can't die until you checked this place out! this is a small gastropub next to cole's and the association (another pub you need to check out). they make these amazing decadent burgers, similar to what you will get at umami burger. i was going to get the black sheep burger, but opted to get the royale with cheese instead because it comes with a fried egg! after the first bite, you definitely can tell they use quality ingredients. the bun is nice and soft and the burger was cooked a perfect medium rare.the best part of the entire meal for me was the beer! this is the first place i have ever been to that served valar morghulis, a beer made for game of thrones! i have been looking for this beer everywhere but they are always sold out. so glad i was able to try it here!i can't give this a perfect 5 star because:1. they open later than most bars (6pm) so i can't come immediately after work. 2. no <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>.3. the service was pretty slow, but i can't blame the waitress. it appeared that she was waiting on the entire restaurant. even though this place is pretty small, they definitely need more than one waitress on a friday night.
don't let the nondescript entrance deter you from giving black sheep a shot. the entrance is overshadowed by cole's next door, but once you find your way inside you'll be greeted by dark, clean-cut, simple modern furniture, a well-balanced selection of booth and stool seats and an efficient bar/ordering counter along a couple large tv's. black sheep aims for a slightly elevated bar scene with a bit more suaveness and hits the mark pretty well. it's reminiscent of less rambunctious doghaus with a little more craft beer, and i find that i enjoy both equally well. the food is straightforward and delicious. they have a variety of burgers and the black sheep burger with gouda and caramelized onions was savory, delicious and just the right amount of messy. at $7 it's the size of a umami burger but not close to the cost. parmesan fries were okay, not the worst and not the best but the carne asada tots were fantastic. i'd order that again in a heartbeat. finally...good selection of beers, with a good range of darker ales/stouts, ipa's and pales. black sheep is up there on my list of casual places to hang out for post-work <span class="highlighted">happy hours</span> in downtown.
