great local bar/restaurant in downtown that's very reasonably priced with plenty of food options! if you're unfamilar with the area, it's actually hard to see from the street because it's somewhat &quot;underground&quot; and below street level. &nbsp;just look for cole's sandwich shop that's next door as well as the association. &nbsp;inside, black sheep has a modern and chic decor, has an moderate amount of seating (25-30approx?), and a very large led tv that plays espn.in terms of the good, the black sheep has many things going for it. &nbsp;expansive menu with around 10 burger options and a few other sandwich options, all of which are very reasonably priced and $8-9 (for la standards, and for &quot;gourmet&quot; burgers). &nbsp;i'm actually surprised that the black sheep hasn't followed the despicable trend like other burger places to charge $12-15-20 for burgers (without any sides of course) like umami and any other non-fast-food burger place. &nbsp;their appetizer list is also quite diverse and all of them seem fairly priced and are definitely sharable between 2 people. &nbsp;of the two burgers i tried, the black sheep burger was definitely more flavorful and left a more memorable experience than the steakhouse burger (which had a weaker cheese and also just non-flavorful sauteed mushrooms). &nbsp;what i liked about the burgers at the black sheet is that the buns aren't oily or too thick and dry; the consistency &amp; taste is similar to a king hawaiian sweet bread roll. &nbsp;the patties were both very thick (at least 1.5&quot;) and the ratio of bun:meat:toppings was 1:2:1, probably optimal! &nbsp;overall, my burger filled me up, but i wasn't struggling to stuff the last few bites as i am with some of the excessively-larger burgers out there. &nbsp;the appetizer that i tried were the parmesan garlic fries ($4) which i thought were &quot;okay.&quot; &nbsp;the main issue i had was that the melted slices of swiss cheese were a bit cold and solidified and thus when i tried to get cheese and fries, i could only get fry and no cheese. the fries themselves were not very hot either, and a few minutes into eating them, they were completely cold :( &nbsp;i couldn't taste very much garlic either, but i'm a huge fan of garlic flavors and don't really think there's such thing as &quot;too much&quot; garlic. &nbsp;their drinks are super cheap and the same as the pricing during <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> at most places; glass of house wine was $4 as was beer. &nbsp;you can get imported bottled beers for $5-6. &nbsp;but $4 for a decent tasting merlot is great value!! &nbsp;i wonder if they have <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> specials....if they did, i would come back to black sheep tonight lol.lastly, my biggest complaint about the black sheet is that it's so understaffed. &nbsp;the poor asian girl visually looked drained and was probably physically exhausted from working there all by herself in the front. &nbsp;she took orders, brought the food to the tables, and even cleaned up after customers all by herself. &nbsp;i wouldn't be too surprised if she helped out in the kitchen too! &nbsp;i don't even know if she's getting her breaks/meals considering there was no one else in sight. &nbsp;lucky for us, it wasn't a busy sunday night , but i can see how if it got busy, things could get ugly. &nbsp;overall, i would definitely go back to the black sheet and try out a few of the other delicious-sounding burgers and side dishes. &nbsp;i just hope that i don't see that poor overworked asian girl by herself during busy time, or i'll have to file a complaint on her behalf to the labor department :p
this bar is as asian as i am. &nbsp;frankly, i don't get it's category or qualifier. &nbsp;they do have 1 or 2 items on the menu that are &quot;asian-inspired&quot; and have sake, but other than that, it's an all-american gastro no different. &nbsp;and, it's really a 4.5 star place to boot.it's dark and small. &nbsp;when i say dark, i should say painted black. &nbsp;it's sparse in decor, which is why black sheep doesn't get a 5 star (along with it's gritty location). &nbsp;with that said, the whole tone of the experience is chill -- both in service and music -- that somehow out of this darkness is light (or is that the glow from the tv's?).amy, the bartender, really helps sets the tone. &nbsp;i don't know how this place rocks without her, but she's really cute and talkative, and was the only person on the staff interfacing with customers. &nbsp;i'd rate her a solid a, and her tats an a+. &nbsp;with a great amount of knowledge, she's able to suggest their ever-changing drafts, sake, and food choices.the main takeaway for me is that i came here, tried a number of items, and want more.speaking of the options...there's lots to like---------------------------------------------------i tried 4 or 5 beers...little samples...because most of what they carry are crafts....and i hadn't heard of them before. &nbsp;in summary, they carry a nice range of flavors -- and i several that were delicious. &nbsp;i was celebrating my bday, so a good friend was buying. &nbsp;yay! &nbsp;drafts vary from $5-7.they have a dozen sake choices. &nbsp;this will have to be part of my next trip to black sheep. &nbsp;unfiltered -- check!food. &nbsp;isn't it always the bottom-line to success?----------------------------------------------------------well, black sheep does it well. &nbsp;burgers, sides, and salads. &nbsp;my buddy and i shared:1 &amp; 2. &nbsp;carne asada tots (4.5 stars), and the parm fries (4.0 stars) -- both were excellent and large portions to share. &nbsp;there were several others, all sounded good. &nbsp;recommend. both.3. &nbsp;the black sheep burger ($8, 4.5 stars): garlic aioli, mushrooms, caramelized onions, gouda cheese, arugula. &nbsp;quality house-blended meat, good brioche bun. &nbsp;the black sheep burgers house blended beef patty, &nbsp;worthy. &nbsp;excellent burger. &nbsp;recommend on quality, flavor, and price. &nbsp;doesn't berger know? &nbsp;see my list.note: didn't try the banh mi sliders - but that's on my list.conclusion--------------small bar, not too busy during the week, good and casual hang with very fair prices that doesn't kill. &nbsp;perhaps on a sat night -- the feel changes. &nbsp;small bar, some tables, and some booths. &nbsp;i really like it as a place to chat, watch a game (no sound), and have quality food at a very fair price.black sheep is no bs -- it's worthy.tips------1. &nbsp;location is next to a couple of known old-time eateries (ie. coles), but also 1 block away from skid row. &nbsp;you can see it from the front door. &nbsp;i parked around the corner for free (after 6pm, meter zone). &nbsp;be careful and aware.2. &nbsp;this not a come early for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> bar kind of place. &nbsp;they open at 6pm most nights. &nbsp;be aware of the <span class="highlighted">hours</span>.
