school is back in session... only this time, it's bigger and better than ever!i walk by the location regularly on my way to and from work and have been counting down the days for the venue to reopen. true to my goody-two-shoes studious self, i was able to go to school before it officially opens to the public.first and foremost, if you remember ps612 from before, this place is more than twice as big and definitely upped the ante in its decor and menu.recess or <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, runs monday - friday from 4 to 6:30pm for food and 7:00pm for drinks. well drinks are $5, food ranges from $4-$7, beers range from $4-$5 a handle (choice of 10 options), half-liter of house wine is $10 (red or white), and half-liter of mohua sauv blanc or filus malbec is $15.**$4 food: dip duo (hummus, baba ghanoush, grilled flatbread), red quinoa salad, parmesan truffle frites (with lemon aioli).**$5 food: chicken sausage, crispy cauliflower, speck &amp; eggs (deviled eggs with crispy prosciutto), and frito pie.**$6 food: schoolyard dog, american sidekicks (3 mini cheeseburgers), crispy naked wings (with buffalo sauce and bleu cheese).**$7 food: crispy ahi tuna tacos (on crispy wonton shells), adobo tacos (2x2 braised short rib &amp; roasted chicken), chorizo mac &amp; cheese, and margherita pizza.brunch is served on saturdays and sundays from 10am-4pm where you can get bottomless drinks (bloody mary, beermosa, mimosa, and michelada) for $10. brunch menu ranges from chicken sausage &amp; cheddar grits to fried jidori chicken &amp; green chili cornbread waffles to fire roasted vegetable hash &amp; eggs to eggs benefit pizza.likewise, they have a rotating live entertainment schedule with various specials:-monday is industry day + night, with 50% off your entire check.-wednesday is live dj with core drafts starting at $1 at 9pm, price going up $1 every 15 minutes until 10pm. from their dinner menu, we tried...**mezze plate ($8) with baba ghanoush, hummus, tapenade, marinated feta, and crispy chickpeas - great to share, free refill of mezze (bread) if desired, hummus was standard, nothing really stood out flavor-wise.**grilled steak salad with white truffle vinaigrette ($17) with prime flat iron steak, wild mushrooms, tomatoes, arugula, shaved fennel, toasted walnuts - i consider salad one of my main food groups and this salad did. not. disappoint. however, as good as it was, i felt like the price was a few bucks higher than what the salad was actually worth.**the huntsman burger ($14) with balsamic onions and huntsman cheese - the balsamic onions elevated the burger from just &quot;good&quot; to &quot;pretty good.&quot;**bbq bison burger ($16) with grass fed bison, whiskey bbq sauce, pepper bacon mushroom topping - good.**brown bag fries ($5) - thin and crispy, good to share!**shaved brussels &amp; kale slaw ($5) with red onions and bleu cheese crumbles - very rich and flavorful, you can definitely taste the bleu cheese.from their cocktail menu, i tried,..**crushed velvet ($10) with blackberry and blueberry reduction, lavendar, and kalsson's gold vodka - a bit on the sweeter side but very good! plus, it's served in a copper mug!**lavender vanilla ($10) with housemade vanilla bitters, lavender simple and four roses small batch - i couldn't taste the lavender or the vanilla as it was overpowered by the whiskey. personally, i wouldn't order this again.we also tried their pb&amp;j cookies (replete with a glass of milk) for dessert, a chalkboard special i believe, and as good as it was, left more to be desired. will return to try their nutella cookie ice cream sandwich.all in all, drinks and food were great, the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> / recess prices are great, and the service was phenomenal. there's plenty of <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> options in the area and i will definitely be adding this to the rotation!
willing to give this place another try/chance.came here on a friday night around 6:30. it was <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> and the bar section was packed. i like the theme of the restaurant as menus looked like note/scrapbooks and napkins looked like notebook paper etc. the alcohol was my favorite part of the evening.to eat i had the crispy ahi tuna tacos for myself. i understand that it's an appetizer but for the price, i felt like it was a weee bit small. i could palm and hide an entire taco in my hand. it was delicious, but either the price needs to be lowered or perhaps add a 5th taco. still hungry, i ordered myself a mezze plate (another appetizer). presentation was great and so were the 5 dipping sauces/sides: baba ghanoush, hummus (can never go wrong with that!), marinated feta, and chickpeas. the bread/pita however was way too hard and overcooked. i thought i was the only one who thought that until i shared and most of my friends were teling me the same. i kind of wanted to let our waitress know but we were planning to leave soon and didn't want to spend more time there.i did mention i am willing to come back here. this time however, no appetizers. just entrees (so i can have a bigger meal and to review), and alcohol of course.anyone know what those protesters outside the restaurant on 9/4 were clamoring about?
let me school you.there's two locations - one in culver city &quot;no. 310&quot; and this new location &quot;no. 213&quot;. i'm lucky i'm by both. it is a great place to eat, drink, and <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> as their menu has a variety with decent pricing. but i noticed the wait in getting your food at this location (and the other) is still a bit slow. the staff and staff service was excellent - very friendly and generous to check on the the order.grilled steak and salad with white truffle vinaigrette ($16) - you must absolutely love truffle to enjoy this salad to the very last bite because there's a lot of truffle flavor. i love truffle anything but after realizing truffle just coats everything i prefer small dosage of truffle. the salad has a nice mix of greens such as wild mushrooms, tomatoes, arugula, shaved fennel, toasted walnuts, grana panado. but you can't really taste the salad as it's overly coated with the truffle flavor. i hope someone from the kitchen watched food network's chopped where the judges dislike truffle oil on the final product for the mere fact that it just hides the real flavor of the raw ingredients. to rid the &quot;truffleness&quot; i dug in my salad for the tomatoes as they gave me that separation. they should mix the dressing with more vinaigrette and a very small dabble of truffle to get a hint of truffle - by the end of my meal my palate was getting bored with the truffle flavor. the steak, on point and no complaint. it was perfectly prepared. $16 seems out of line for this pretty salad and think it needs to be shaved down because it felt like a worthy $12 salad in my opinion. recommend. there will be no hesitation to travel 57 floors down for eats around the corner.until the next review...
