i came here after getting some dinner in little tokyo. we wanted to just relax and drink some cocktails, thus wolf and crane appeared on our yelp. we made it just in time for the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> and we seated ourselves onto the bar. i quickly noticed the japanese inspired decor. there was a theme revolving around japanese whiskey for their were multiple specialities that featured the whiskey. i ordered myself the bar's interpretation of a moscow mule; however their vodka was replaced with whiskey. i did not enjoy the drink unfortunately. i also ordered one of the craft beers, and it was quite refreshing (forgot the name). after a while, the booze began to kick in and i needed to use the restroom. i thought it was interesting that they had manga snippets as the design in their restroom. once of the factors that made us leave early would be the ambience at the bar. it was strangely empty, and i remember customers coming into the bar with their dogs. i do not mind pets, but it can be awkward having a dog bark at you while you are drinking some whiskey indoors. i would tell the owner to stick to the classics for the cocktails, and to find a way to create a more lively and comfortable atmosphere for the bar.
with shochu and sake being the beverages of choice in little tokyo, there aren't too many places that have a fully stocked bar within the area. with that being said, wolf &amp; crane bar would be the first pub i would hit. why? three reasons.(1) clean. i don't know if the place has been open for long, but it's really tidy. including, the restrooms. soft wooden decor, small sized bar area, with several seats available. not a huge venue, but there's a make shift smoking patio in the front, for those of you that favor the vape and cigarettes. once inside, to the left, there's a few tables to hold a decent sized group. think about a casual weekday <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> or even a late sunday get together. cozy, but loud and vibrant enough to get the mingling started.(2) music. nothing gets me thinking more about the 80's than this hit song by the band simple minds, called &quot;don't you (forget about me).&quot; the popular flick called the breakfast club is what made this song famous. also, i believe i heard the cure as well. the song - &quot;pictures of you&quot; was a great single by the british rock band from their 1989 album disintegration. beats like this only add to the intrigue of this dive bar. be there or be square, right?(3) people. ranging from middle aged professionals, the cool nerds, and an ever growing rise of the hipsters. many of my fellow yelpers also seem to frequent this place as well - joe p, sasi m, helena h, joseph a, ru c, christine t, justin y, catalina t, and chanel c. peeps with personality and those that would definitely get the party started proper. i even ran into marvy s during my last visit. of all the random places! but, with my luck, i meet the best kind of people.with semi stiff drinks at prices that are never too stiff, why wouldn't i stop by here for a quick beverage to relieve my quenching thirst? remember, it's ok to indulge in alcohol. not to get too technical, but according to chemistry, alcohol is a solution.
pretty cool bar. very chill. the place is not too crowded or too loud. the bartenders are nice and prompt. drinks are affordable and taste pretty decent. heck, even the restrooms are clean!! this is for sure a nice little hidden gem in little tokyo that i sure hope to visit more often. the vibe of the place is truly awesome! there is no pressure to look or act a certain way. everyone is very friendly and they have some cool jams playing. heard they have a dj every now and then as well. no real dress code but cmon, you girls know you wanna dress up and you guys know you wanna look fly, anything goes here. everyone is very welcoming. even the bouncer checking ids was really nice. this place is open from 3pm to 2am on the weekends and weekdays from 5pm until 2am. there is even a <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> monday through friday from 5pm-7pm. drinks:wolf and crane has a good range of drinks. anything from beer (such as sapporo, el segundo ipa, craftsman heavenly hef and some ales), wines, mixed drinks you will find it there, they even sell cigarettes!!!*gin trap - $10gin, tonic and a hint of grapefruit. very refreshing. nice gin taste without being a watered down drink. if you like the bitter taste with a little sweetness of grapefruit, i would highly recommend this drink. the ingredients are well combined in which neither flavors overpowers each other (good job, cute bartender)*moscow mule (not sure how much this one was since i didn't get the first round)the drink was very eh.. i've had better. it wasn't one of the best ones i've had. something about the taste was just off. maybe too much ginger beer in mine? there seemed to have been way too much ginger beer and not enough vodka for my taste. *baja buck - $9my favorite drink of the night. the tequila, grape fruit and ginger beer made this drink a tasty buzz for me. there is a hint of lime of course to go with it as well. the ginger beer here was less than with the moscow mule. you do get the hint of tequila in it making it an outstanding drink and that grape fruit flavor in there just surprises you. *old fashionnot bad! very very smooth and i'm not really a whiskey drinker but this particular glass i shared was tasty. it was garnished with a little cherry piece on top that i was told was there to enhance the taste of the drink. i don't recall the brand of whiskey they used to make the drink but if i remember it, i will update this with that information.
perhaps you, like me, spot the rather snazzy neon origami above a door and outdoor patio illuminated from above with strung lights and think &quot;push.&quot; then maybe &quot;pull?&quot; then you start to realize this door isn't going to open. &nbsp;the real entrance 50 ft. over is unmarked, without sign and even among the staff looks like it might belong to a construction project. &nbsp;i suppose it feels a little more like a bar or some underground nightclub. &nbsp;but there are going to be a whole lot of people pushing on that door. &nbsp;wolf &amp; crane is a new watering hole (and exclusively that) in little tokyo. &nbsp;don't expect a large selection of japanese whiskey or sake-inspired this or asian flavors that -- this is a fairly on-trend couple of cocktails and craft brews sort of establishment. &nbsp;even the japanese decorations on the inside (the random manga wallpaper, various prints) feel a little bit like an afterthought. &nbsp;it has kind of rustic look some popular amongst the kids these days, but i kid. &nbsp;the interior is nice, dark with ropes dividing a more intimate small benches area from the main bar and high tops and where you'll find that on-trend warehouse lighting. &nbsp;many people comment on the smooth bar, made of light wood and covered in epoxy which helps give it its matte look, i learned surprisingly but just overhearing and not by the hard investigative reporting you've come to expect from yelp.it is nice, casual and rather simple. &nbsp;it's not cheesy. &nbsp;it is not, say, ebanos for example. &nbsp;there's a lot of johnnie red above the bar. the specials both feature it one with soda. one with a sapporo. &nbsp;there too are tvs above the bar, housed in mirrored boxes. &nbsp;i guess the theory is that after a certain time they'll get turned off and tah-dah, it's like the tvs never existed and people will have to actually talk to each other. &nbsp;i like this idea. &nbsp;this seems like a fine idea. &nbsp;but i wonder how long it will be before someone complains that such and such a game isn't over yet, or this or that. &nbsp;it won't be that long. &nbsp;still, i like the sentiment. &nbsp;house cocktails run $9-10 and lean towards the sweeter side. most end in soda. and yes fernet makes an appearance. &nbsp;this drink ($10) is mostly fernet and root beer. &nbsp;and tastes like well, bitter root beer. &nbsp;which isn't exactly a bad thing. &nbsp;i read that fernet is a favorite amongst bartenders just because no one really knows what to do with it. &nbsp;this lends itself well to trying new things and there's a little bit of a conversation starter this. &nbsp;indeed, in my short time in the bar a half dozen or so of the house 'highballs' of the stuff go out. &nbsp;<span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> runs from 5-7 with $5 netting you one of several things: wells, a pair of wines and a pair of beers. &nbsp;normally, the 10 beers on tap (no word on anything in bottles) run $5-8 and wines run $7-11. there's a section on the menu for else. &nbsp;snacks are 2. &nbsp;little bagged japanese snacks. &nbsp;and cigarettes ($10). &nbsp;it turns out what i assumed was the entrance is a smoking patio. &nbsp;this makes sense in hindsight and you smokers out there, know smokes are available behind the bar. &nbsp;i've moved onto my second when a man who looks like he has some war stories bellies up to the bar and gets a double of the johnnie. &nbsp;in a bar filled with mostly 20 and 30-somethings i'm comforted that this sort of character has appeared. &nbsp;but downtown is usually good about this sort of thing.
