came to celebrate my birthday on a saturday afternoon during some <span class="highlighted">hour</span> which the entire menu isn't available, only <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. we were seated quickly and the hostess was super friendly, allowing us to sit at a table near the bar since we had a larger party. we ordered a few of the appetizers which came out really quick. the food was great and the guac was amazing, just like everyone said. we had the strawberry basil margarita which i loved. the server was also the only bartender and since it was <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> it was a little chaotic and he did seem very overwhelmed.i probably would give this place more stars if we hadn't noticed something which made us all lose our appetites... when the server, who had very long hair, went to pick up food from the back station he pulled his hair lose and began scratching his head. like really going at it. okay, that's fine we all get itchy but pleaseeeee wash your hands. he absolutely failed to do so. he tied it back up, grabbed the food and presented it to customers at the bar. barf. i've worked in restaurants before, there is a certification class everyone must take to be able to work in a restaurant, so there is really no excuse. it's against health code violations and not to mention common sanitation habits. i was completely shocked to see this type of thing right before my own eyes. at that point we didn't even care to mention it was my birthday to receive any complimentary dessert. no thanks.
fun place to celebrate my sister's birthday during her visit to la! we always have to indulge her craving for &quot;mexican&quot; food when she's visiting as good mexican food is still hard to find in dc where she lives. we got here around 6 pm, so the restaurant hasn't totally filled up yet, but by the time we left, the place was hoppin'! &nbsp;unfortunately, we were seated near the kitchen and it was a hot day, so we were a little warm in our spot. or maybe it was that yummy margarita that was responsible for that extra heat i was feeling? who knows? in any case, get a pitcher of their margarita! it's nice and strong and perfect for a group of 4-5 people! we ordered the guac and the queso with chorizo for the table to start. yum! the queso was runnier than i would have liked but who can resist such cheesy goodness? the chips were just perfect for dipping. the celebrant was very <span class="highlighted">happy</span>, despite being bummed at first for missing their super nacho <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, but we had chips, guac and queso on the table, so she was able to create her own nacho dish! my husband and i shared the mondongo which had oxtails, tripe, and chickpeas. i liked the oxtail, but this dish had too much chickpeas! it should have had more broth and less chickpeas. it came with flour tortillas too but we didn't even touch that as we were on the verge of being too full at that point. also, not a good dish to order when you're feeling warm. it's more of a winter dish. the others ordered taquitos, mom's enchiladas with borracho beans and rice and a short rib chalupa. they were all <span class="highlighted">happy</span> with their food. we also ordered the cauliflower with cilantro pesto dish and boy, was that good! it'll make you a cauliflower lover, if you're not already. we didn't have dessert with all that food we had. we were definitely primed though to continue our celebration at another bar a few blocks away. next time, super nacho <span class="highlighted">hour</span> and more of that margarita!!!
i really only have 2 words to sum this place up: puffy tacos! aka sean &quot;puffy&quot; tacos aka diddy t's aka puffy t's aka p. tacs shakur aka the t, the a, the c, the o the s... that's tacos -- hold up, puff tacos!!!i wouldn't order anything else from bar ama unless you are a vegan. &nbsp;if you are a vegan, i feel bad for you son, but in this case, you have 99 problems but fake queso ain't one! &nbsp;the cashew queso is pretty damn good too! i personally add chorizo to it, but i'm not a hell burning hippy vegan. &nbsp;their regular queso dip is even more delish and their chips are crisp and hold a lot of dip. &nbsp;i took a to go bag home to eat while watching the game the next day... let's just say they didn't make it to the next day!as for the ambiance. &nbsp;this is a great place to take a date. &nbsp;disclaimer: you should know that approximately 90% of the people in this establishment are very good looking. &nbsp;this includes the staff. &nbsp;at one point i looked around and said to my date, cathie, &quot;i might not be the best looking person in here&quot;. &nbsp;she looked around and re-assured me i was. &nbsp;although, jeremy, one of their best waiters is someone you definitely wouldn't kick out of bed for eating crackers... or bar ama tortilla chips!all this talk, i think i will go there tonight for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> and one of their stiff cocktails! &nbsp;see you there!
looked forward to visiting this tex-mex restaurant for a while since i'm originally from texas and miss my style of mexican food. overall, it was really good, if not completely satisfying.we got there early for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, which was great. reasonably priced drinks and some appetizers. the nachos were probably my favorite part of the evening. once we sat down, we had the infamous puffy tacos, which i thought lived up to the hype. these were not part of my tex-mex history, but i enjoyed them.my biggest anticipation was also my biggest disappointment. the queso. in texas, it's quite common to have this ooey-gooey cheese dip, often made from something like velveeta. &nbsp;most restaurants here in los angeles serve something that is less a dip and more like melted cheese. this queso just didn't have much taste. i get that it's supposed to be more high-end, but i expect at least the same amount or more flavor.if i lived closer to downtown i would definitely be back a lot more!
i went in for lunch and it was relatively busy for a tuesday afternoon with what seemed to be the business crowds from surrounding companies. we decided to have a seat at the bar since it was open and the table offered was crappy. the bartender was so nice and offered up some great recommendations. he even let us sample some of the mezcal and beer that we asked about even though we both already had cocktails. this is not your normal &quot;mexican&quot; restaurant and i believe they are actually marketed as &quot;tex-mex&quot;. i was so disappointed that the puffy tacos that we drove out for, were no longer available so i opted for the carne tacos and my boyfriend had the shrimp ones. both were really good, but i really wanted those adobada and pineapple ones.we also shared the following items: yellowtail ceviche, chicharron, queso with chorizo. on top of this, we had 2 cocktails each. while everything was yummy, i found the $125 bill to be excessive for lunch. especially for tex mex. i would come back when they offer a <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> as i don't think its a drive for that price from the west side.
given that the name reminds me of the spanish &quot;amar&quot;, i think i could really come to love this bar. it's casual, but not so much so that you wouldn't want to come here for a special occasion. in fact, the night i visited a large group was also there celebrating a birthday. they got lucky though, in terms of seating space it's a pretty small area. i don't think the bar would be able to accommodate groups larger than 12 people, and even then only two large groups at a time. the space was so compact that my party was seated very close to another couple, and it was a bit difficult tuning out their conversation (since we were basically sitting at the same table). of course, we were there during prime visiting <span class="highlighted">hours</span> on a friday night - so it might not always get that full. before bar ama, i considered myself the type who can't enjoy whiskey. and then i tried their snake's blood. this was one of the best cocktails i've had in recent memory, and i would come back solely for this drink. beware, the reason i liked it is because it was sweet and flavorful and didn't taste like whiskey!i also enjoyed the tex-mex queso for the table, something like a fancy 3-layer dip for our nachos. i love their family-style section of the menu, although i opted for a lighter jicama salad. their portions in general are very generous; my salad was bright, filling, and the pomegranate was lovely! it was a great choice next to the heavier cheese dip and alcoholic drinks. i'm curious about their mole eggplant and hope to have the courage to try it next time - maybe i need to order a snake's blood or two before ordering food!. overall, this bar may be better-suited for a <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> visit with a smaller group of people. but still this could be the beginning of a beautiful thing - si el bar ama a steph, tal vez se&aacute; que steph ama al bar!
as a fan of b&auml;co mercat, i wasn't too impressed with bar am&aacute;.with reservations, we were quickly seated by the hostess stand. i'd originally come for the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, super nacho <span class="highlighted">hour</span>, but found out through our server that it was only at the bar. the menu is huge, so we spent a good 10-minutes perusing it. eventually, my friends decided they were too indecisive and that i should order for everyone.for drinks, we got two pitchers of beer and for myself, a pineapple ginger non-alcoholic beverage, which was very tasty. between the four of us, we ordered three dishes recommended by our server. she assured us this was enough food for our group. it was not enough.we started off with cauliflower &amp; cilantro pesto ($11), which was my favorite dish of the night. i love cauliflower to begin with, but the sauce was divine. next, we had the pork belly chicharr&oacute;n ($12), which was unmemorable. it was basically two thick slices of pork belly served in a bowl of chile-poblano cream, so it was difficult to split four-ways. lastly, for our main, we went family-style and got am&aacute;'s steak ranchero ($44) off the la familia menu. served with huge pieces of bacon, potato wedges, mushrooms, and one egg, again, it was hard to divide among our group. the steak was cut into strips, so it was easy for everyone to grab their share, but one egg? come on. what are we supposed to do with one egg? otherwise, this was a very good dish. slightly spicy, all the ingredients mixed well together and had abundant flavor. but i'd split this with one other person, not three.the food is good and josef centeno does tex-mex well. with that said, i can't justify paying so much for tex-mex tapas. centeno won me over with b&auml;co mercat, but unfortunately, i'm in no hurry to return to bar am&aacute;.
came here yesterday for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. originally i was extremely excited because i had heard so much about this place and their vegan options. my friend and i walked in a little after 5:30 the hostess was on the phone and just ignored us while she was on the phone. i'm sure she was taking reservations but most restaurants i've been to the hostess at least motions or nods to acknowledge you. we decided to head to the bar, big mistake. we waited for a pretty long time for the bartender to even acknowledge us. after over 10 mins of waiting she finally said, i'll be right with you ladies. she sounded kind of annoyed, mind you the place had just opened. there weren't that many people there, so i couldn't understand why it took so long to even be spoken to. when she finally came to take our order we ordered our food and drinks together. our food was served before our drinks. food was delicious! my friend had the super nachos and i had the guacamole. when our drinks were served they were the wrong drinks! after all that waiting she had mixed up our order with the person to the right of us. finally her coworker with the pink hair took over, she was great made our drinks and apologized for the mix up. after we finished our food the pink haired bartender asked me if there was something else she could get us. i told her to hold off on the check until my friend returned from the restroom, she said no problem. seconds later the original bartender we had brought the check over, so she made the decision for us. i guess we won't be ordering anything else.food was good but not worth the poor service to be honest, two appetizers and two cocktails the bill was almost $40. there's plenty of other mexican food spots in los angeles with better service that justify the cost. if i do come again i will not be sitting at the bar.
went there for lunch the other day. staff was nice. we had a margaritas-kind of small but tasty.tried the squash blossom appetizer. it was amazing... kind of small again. 4 bites for $11. i know, amazing food that is labor intensive... still we inhaled $11 in less than 1 minute.we ordered the chile relleno and the mole enchiladas with picadillo added for entrees . they came and my first thought was &quot;oh thats small, didn't know it was a la carte.&quot;it's just two enchiladas and just one chill relleno.i ordered beans and rice on the side which was a good amount with sausage &nbsp;added.i also had to ask for chips which if we had from the beginning might have filled us up a bit. so we were finally good on quantity and happily devouring our food. the flavors are amazing. i just didn't know it was going to be tapas portion entrees.i'm used to the small portions from so many restaurants we go to but this is tex- mex. i'm from austin and have eaten a lot of tex- mex in my life. never left hungry.so i had to try the sopapillas for dessert and was thoroughly let down. there were 3 puffy sopapillas that deflated to a wafer thin honey soaked eh experience. $8 really?they cost nothing. you get a basket of unlimited sopapillas at restaurants in austin. i know we are not there but really? anyway, bill came out to about $80 for lunch and with tip one on the most expensive lunches i've eaten where i left still wishing for more food. i would not go here really hungry again. i would come back but maybe for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> or with friends for pitcher of margaritas and tacos. just too expensive for what it was. it wouldn't kill them to give out chips and a side with entrees.tex mex just doesn't work a la carte.
this place was a great find on one of nights wandering around and baco mercat was too packed. the hostess there ended up directing us to here instead and wouldn't you know, it's owned by the same people. &nbsp;it's a small quaint little hole in the wall and is usually quite packed but we got lucky because somebody apparently cancelled a reservation (you'll definitely want to though, this place is not only packed, but delicious!).unfortunately, my review on this will be a little bit biased since i came here after a little bit of drinking and even though my friends got us lost to baco mercat so our walk was a bit longer than i thought, we continued to drink more after we arrived (but i don't think that affected my taste buds any). &nbsp;it was the first time we had ever eaten there so we decided to have our waiter provide us with a few suggestions which were all very good. &nbsp;it's a tapas place here so it's all meant to be shared.we started off with the guacamole which is made to order and served in a stone bowl. it was chunky (the way it should be!) and they were more than <span class="highlighted">happy</span> to refill us on their homemade tortillas whenever we ran out. we also got the fried brussel sprouts which had a very tiny kick to them and wasn't too oily. &nbsp;we also ordered the borracho beans &amp; rice as well as some tacos and it was all very delicious. for a place that advertises tex-mex, i'd probably say this is more of a mexican fusion type bar.if you look at the rest of the menu though, they've got some pretty crazy stuff out there (mondongo? what!? albondigas?? pork belly chicharron!?!?)it is a tad bit pricey and i'm not sure if they have a <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, but it's got a little of the hipster feel and still nice enough to bring a date on.
as a longtime resident of echo park and downtown los angeles, in my opinion bar am&aacute;, where i was a regular for nearly two years from the moment it opened, exemplifies an establishment that caters in balanced fashion to both locals and visitors to downtown l.a. living half a block away, i enjoyed my many meals and <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> deals here. the cocktails are phenomenal. the bartenders are cool. some of them make quite the theatre out of shaking their cocktails. the waitstaff are efficient and friendly. they work well as a team.and the food... josef's creations are inventive and daring too. i'm pescatarian, so my favorites are the cilantro-pesto cauliflower, the brussels sprouts, the mol&eacute; egglplant, the puffy tacos (which you can still order but are no longer on the menu -- potato is only $6 and the shrimp is also excellent), the salads, the mol&eacute; enchilada. i'm big on sauces and theirs are varied and well matched to the dishes.their tex mex queso or guacamole with chips satisfy deep cravings. for brunch, try the migas or huevos rancheros. the beans with kielbasa (i have cheated, and it was worth it) are served all day. bar am&aacute; now serves enchiladas vegan style with a housemade cashew cheese. the green chicken &quot;mom's&quot; enchiladas are superb. yummy food all around, lots of healthy and tasty vegetable dishes, and even more for meat eaters. bar am&aacute; is already an l.a. institution. you do have to know the vibe. make a reservation if you are not a regular.
as a longtime resident of echo park and downtown los angeles, in my opinion bar am&aacute;, where i was a regular for nearly two years from the moment it opened, exemplifies an establishment that caters in balanced fashion to both locals and visitors to downtown l.a. living half a block away, i enjoyed my many meals and <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> deals here. the cocktails are phenomenal. the bartenders are cool. some of them make quite the theatre out of shaking their cocktails. the waitstaff are efficient and friendly. they work well as a team.and the food... josef's creations are inventive and daring too. i'm pescatarian, so my favorites are the cilantro-pesto cauliflower, the brussels sprouts, the mol&eacute; egglplant, the puffy tacos (which you can still order but are no longer on the menu -- potato is only $6 and the shrimp is also excellent), the salads, the mol&eacute; enchilada. i'm big on sauces and theirs are varied and well matched to the dishes.their tex mex queso or guacamole with chips satisfy deep cravings. for brunch, try the migas or huevos rancheros. the beans with kielbasa (i have cheated, and it was worth it) are served all day. bar am&aacute; now serves enchiladas vegan style with a housemade cashew cheese. the green chicken &quot;mom's&quot; enchiladas are superb. yummy food all around, lots of healthy and tasty vegetable dishes, and even more for meat eaters. bar am&aacute; is already an l.a. institution. you do have to know the vibe. make a reservation if you are not a regular.
maybe i'm being a little harsh with 3 stars, but i think this place is over-hyped! &nbsp;the food was good but was it 4 or 5 star good? &nbsp;some of the dishes were, but not all, which is why the 3 stars. &nbsp;the service was great though and we got some recommendations from our waiter, which was helpful. &nbsp;we ordered the tex mex queso to start ($9 for what tasted like velveeta cheese with a small side of avocado, sour cream and salsa with tortilla chips), fried brussels sprouts ($11 - for brussels sprouts?!), seared lengua ($15 - this was actually really good) and mom's green enchiladas ($13 - not bad). &nbsp;all the dishes were a bit heavy and even the brussels sprouts didn't give me that light refreshing feeling because of the cheese. &nbsp;i felt like some items were overpriced (the tex mex queso and the brussels sprouts). &nbsp;between two people (we only ordered one drink off the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> menu) our bill came out to about $38/person (this included tax and tip)...pricey if you ask me. &nbsp;this is what happens with all &quot;tapas&quot; places. &nbsp;you have to order double of what you would normally order at a regular restaurant to be satisfied but the prices for each dish are higher or the same as what it would be for an entree dish someplace else. &nbsp;it's hard for me to give tapas places rave reviews unless every dish we ordered was fantastic, which was not the case here. &nbsp;just my pov...sorry.
josef centeno is probably my favorite chef in the downtown la area right now. &nbsp;if i could take this man home-and have him cook all my meals for me- i would. &nbsp;my first time at bar am&aacute; was at the beginning of the summer, about six months after it's opening. located in the historic core of downtown la (a block or two away from the last book store-a must visit), bar am&aacute; is the essence of home style tex-mex cuisine. &nbsp;the layout of the restaurant is small and compact, a bar off to the left, open kitchen in the back and small tables filling the rest of the space in between. &nbsp;the ambiance is casual and hip; dates, families, coworkers, friends-it is great for everyone.bar am&aacute; offers a tex- mex bento lunch box: chips, burrito, and a b&auml;co pop of your choice. &nbsp;it's a great value, very filling, and more importantly a treat for your taste buds. &nbsp;the original b&auml;co pop has flavors reminiscent of ginger, orange, and &nbsp;juniper. &nbsp;it is so refreshingly amazing. another one of my favorites when i am in the mood for something sweeter is the pineapple &amp; canela b&auml;co pop-it is the perfect combination of sweet and spice; it has a great after taste unlike other sweet drinks which can leave your mouth feeling gritty. &nbsp;the chips and salsa are traditional and freshly made. &nbsp;the burrito is large (nothing like the mass that is a chipotle burrito) but not so big that you will be put ito a food coma. &nbsp;it has great flavor and is grilled to be slightly crispy so that it does not fall apart or drip.their take on <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> is called &nbsp;&quot;super nacho <span class="highlighted">hour</span>&quot;. &nbsp;the menu is served at the bar; service can be a little slow here, but once the food starts coming out, you will not care. &nbsp;the heaping plate of nachos are covered in their house made tex-mex queso which is to die for. &nbsp;another of my go-to dishes on the super nacho <span class="highlighted">hour</span> menu is the green calabacitas taco. &nbsp;it is a very large soft taco filled with shredded green squash, zuchinni, kale, onions cooked in a mild sauce. the puffy taco. &nbsp;there are a few options for the filling, but my favorites are the shrimp and the potato. &nbsp;the shrimp is perfectly de-veined (which is huge pet peeve of mine), topped with a creamy, flavorful sauce, and the usual taco fixins'. &nbsp;the potato puffy taco has nice chunks of fried golden potatoes that are seasoned and also topped with the sauce and fixins'. &nbsp;the shell itself is a little greasy, but it is fried, so it's to be expected. guacamole- made to order to your desirable taste. &nbsp;it's perfect for sharing if you are on a date or with a group. &nbsp; i feel like the portion size has decreased since my first time there, but because bar am&aacute; is a small plate styled restaurant, it makes sense so you have room for their other options.the vegetables served at bar am&aacute; are seasonal. &nbsp;some of the best vegetable dishes i have had here: &nbsp;cauliflower and cilantro pesto, asparagus &amp; crema, spaghetti squash, roasted sweet potato, blistered baby squash (a similar dish is offered at b&auml;co mercat), and the fried brussel sprouts. &nbsp;i never thought to pair cauliflower with pesto, but the two are so harmonious together. the spaghetti squash is &nbsp;served in a medium-sized bowl and looks like orange spaghetti mush, but it tastes incredible. &nbsp;it is a little on the sweeter side, but it has hints of cojita and lime, the yam is more noticeable and there is persillade crumbled on top. &nbsp;the roasted sweet potato is double roasted, cut in half, spread with butter, drizzled with honey and sprinkled with sea salt and tastes like thanksgiving. again, this dish is on the sweeter side, but is balanced by the sea salt.am&aacute;'s favorites are the &quot;main entr&eacute;e&quot; selections. i have tried the mom's green enchiladas, which were way too cheesey for me. &nbsp;if you love cheese though, this is the dish for you. &nbsp;recently he has added a variety of taquitos to the favorites section. &nbsp;i had the corn grit ones not too long ago-amazing. &nbsp; i can't wait to go back and try the other ones offered, such as lobster and duck! &nbsp;my two favorite desserts at bar am&aacute; are the leche quemada pudding and the rice pudding. &nbsp;the leche quemada is so rich and caramelly. &nbsp;centeno turned it into a pudding served on a layer of graham crakers and topped with fennel pollen and crushed almonds-each bite leaves you pining for more. &nbsp;the rice pudding is traditional. it has the perfect amount of cinnamon, caramel and graham cracker; it is so rich and delectable-the perfect way to end your meal if you have enough room left.bar am&aacute; is my place to eat at when i want a delicious, home style cooked meal. &nbsp;centeno does not disappoint and the location is prime. &nbsp;parking has never been an issue, and it is pretty walkable from the city center. bar am&aacute; has something for everyone-vegetarian and meat lovers; so do not pass it up, your stomach will thank you later.
i was so excited to finally try bar ama yesterday, and boy was i disappointed. i don't even know where to begin...all i know is that as much as i wanted to write a review when i got home yesterday, i thought better of it because i was still so bothered about my meal and experience. we met friends there for brunch, and when we got there we were the only ones in the place because our reservation was for shortly after they opened. we got there after our friends, so our waiter may have introduced himself to them, but not to us, so i never got his name. if i had, you would be seeing it a lot in this review even though we rarely saw him in our <span class="highlighted">hour</span> and a half at our table. he was medium height, dark wavy-ish hair, glasses, skinny jeans and a look that let us know he had just gotten out of bed and really didn't want to be there. i asked for a coke, only to learn that they did not have normal soda there, but instead their own brand. he started rattling off flavors, and i kept shaking my head to let him know i didn't want those. he then stopped and asked if he should even continue. so, yeah...that was awesome. i didn't realize the servers were trained to be rude to customers, but whatever. i asked him to continue and ordered the rootbeer chocolate soda which was meh.when we were just about ready to order, we asked what the more popular menu items were, and once again our hipster waiter was too cool for school, and basically told us that everything on the menu was popular. my husband asked about the breakfast tacos and if he could mix and match, to which he was promptly told 'no', with no explanation. so, he asked about another dish, which apparently if you just order it, and don't ask questions, it comes served cold, with hot tortillas to warm the food. so my husband opted for the breakfast potato and egg tacos, and i ordered the huevos rancheros. here is the description of the huevos rancheros on the menu: smoked ham hock, fried eggs, beans. that 's all it says. i didn't think to ask many questions since it seemed self explanatory and our waiter seemed less then <span class="highlighted">happy</span> to answer any type of question.the food takes a long time, so we asked for chips and salsa to which our waiter said ' it's not something we just do, but if asked for we can bring some to you...but we don't have salsa we have a romesco sauce'. just bring us the chips and what was clearly salsa and treat us like we aren't annoying you in your house.so, when our food came, my eggs were clearly sunny side up. so, i asked him why my eggs were cooked that way when the menu said the eggs were fried, and he said 'oh ,they are fried, they are pan fried' . now, there is a huge difference between fried and pan fried eggs, but regardless of that, i told him that i wanted my eggs fried and he said to me again ' they are' and proceeded to walk away not to be seen again for 35 minutes. there was also no mention of cilantro in my meal description and there was a ton...i am one of those 'i hate cilantro people' but since i couldn't seem to find our waiter and no one was coming near our table, i lightly picked at my food. my husband is from texas and was excited for what was supposed to be authentic tex-mex. he did not care for the food in the slightest. his two tacos were filled with cabbage and sour cream and not much egg and potato...and what egg and potato were in there were soggy. he didn't even finish the two tacos that were on his plate.when we finally got our waiter's attention to ask for the check, it was clear as day that i didn't eat my food, however he ignored that completely..didn't ask how any of our meals were...didn't ask if i wanted a box even. just asked if we were ready for the check. i walked out side so i wouldn't yell or make a scene because i am not like that, but i was livid at that point. for such a lauded restaurant, it was one of the worst experiences i have ever had while dining out in los angeles....and that is saying a lot.
