<span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> review:background: i work in cal plaza. i'm a dedicated hh attendee of this location's former self: casa because, to be honest it meets basic criteria of: convenient, reasonable prices, good <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> options, lots of young business professionals to&quot; people-watch&quot; and talk with. i was sad to see casa go (despite my nasty yelp review) and curious to see what a &quot;high end sandwich place&quot; could possibly look like considering its sister establishment: &quot;mendocino farms&quot; was already pretty fancy and pricey.food:i had one item. why am i writing a review if i've only had one food item? b/c it was that...damn...good... french (onion short rib) dip. find it on the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> menu for $8. served on slightly grilled kings hawaiian bread, this sandwich is lightly stuffed w/ savory pieces of short rib that shred apart into your mouth like god intended. after one bite i stopped and reveled in the sweet grilled onions, hearty shreds of beef and salty... creamy.... gruyere... all swirling around in my mouth resulting in pure ecstasy. i took another bite and the crunch of the crouton, strategically placed in the center of the sandwich, just overwhelmed my senses and made me giggle with delight. this sandwich is all i need to start a friday off right..their menu seemed so complicated. i was hesitant to try anything with such bold flavors as &quot;mustard pickle slaw&quot; , &quot;sesame ginger&quot; and &quot;candied jalapenos&quot; but as my partner in crime stated, &quot;the real test is in your tastebuds&quot; (or some butchered rendition of that.)... blue cow has passed w/ flying colors.service:the manager there is really great. i'm not his friend. i don't know his name. i honestly mean this as a random patron: he is cognizant of a restaurant's need to deliver customer satisfaction and how to provide it.. we stopped by to &quot;pick up &quot; lunch and found out, sadly, they aren't doing &quot;to-go&quot; lunch just yet. so when my coworker and i came for a little <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> later that day, the bartender told us the first round was on them (because the manager remembered us and wanted to make up for our lunch time disappointment). that is just plain above and beyond.. the place has our loyal patronage already and he knows it. i mean, you've all been there: going to a place you don't love just b/c it's convenient, close to the office, cheap, etc.. so for this guy to go the extra mile to make sure we were treated well was just so wonderful and (sadly) unexpected for an la establishment.overall:i like the blue cow look. the lighter colored walls (the dark brown of casa was a little cave-like). the old leather couch and comfy chairs. the food (i've tried so far) and the comprehensive <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> drinks menu with beer, wine, and at least 4 cocktails that are not to be underestimated. i was a little scared to see my hh staple close and change so dramatically. my fear is absolved and morphed into eager anticipation for what blue cow has to offer. updated review to come, once i get a little more familiar with my new neighbor.
