i would describe plan check as contemporary american bar food. &nbsp;it is located in a great space at 1111 wilshire just a little bit west of downtown. &nbsp;the atmosphere of the restaurant is definitely trendy, but homey and casual. &nbsp;we went for the end of <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> on a friday evening at about 6:30pm. &nbsp;we sat at the communal table overlooking wilshire. &nbsp;we had a great server by the name of taylor (i believe...or was it tyler). &nbsp;he was very helpful, attentive, and gave great recommendations!the food was probably the best bar food, i have yet to have in los angeles. &nbsp;we started off with an appetizer of the chili cheese fries, and then we shared one chefs favorite burger and one southern fry. &nbsp;they were both delicious, had unique and amazing flavorful tastes in every bite, and just couldn't find a single thing i didn't like.i will definitely return to plan check, as i really cannot put my finger on one single detriment. this was a great start to an awesome evening.
i've been to plan check twice. overall, i'm definitely coming back. it's a great place to grab dinner after work with a couple of friends or even large groups. here's a list of pros and cons based on my past two visits:pros:- i've ordered the plan check burger both times because it's a delicious, juicy and hearty burger. i'm looking forward to tasting the other burgers/sandwiches/dishes.- you shouldn't have a long wait if you get there on an early evening weeknight (except for friday maybe). the staff is friendly and will try their best to accommodate large groups.- they have a great beverage selection and <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> deals.- everything's served in cast iron. am i the only one who thinks this is awesome and makes everything taste better?cons:- street parking (it's downtown la, so no surprise). if you're lucky, you'll find metered street parking (free after 6pm) on wilshire or beaudry.- some of their menu items just aren't worth ordering again. for example, the $3 beer nuts (which i'd expect to be like a free appetizer), the $6.50 veggie chips (hard and stale tasting, although the avocado dip was good), and the dessert which was pretty underwhelming.
this place only opened 7 days ago??i would've never guessed, especially with the smooth way they're handling the suddenly influx of hello kitty fans during the hungry hunt. &nbsp;i'm used to slow service, wrong orders, and other mishaps during opening week of restaurants. hey, shit happens, but not here! &nbsp;the servers and the manager are very attentive and friendly. &nbsp;whenever we asked our serer, connor, for something, he was sweet as can be and always got back to us promptly. &nbsp;my group had the hello kitty bento, which was off menu, but the burger was very delicious! my only feedback would be that the burger and the tuna salad were a tad on the salty side, and the buns could be improved, but the important part - the meat- had great flavor and was nice and juicy. &nbsp;the dessert that came with the bento was amazing too!! some sort of fluffy flaky donut contraption. love it. kudos to plan check for keeping their product consistent despite the rush of getting orders out. &nbsp;will definitely be back to try the regular burgers!p.s. all day <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> sunday during football season!
