i really wanted to love this place, especially since i was really excited to come here for dine la <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> week. but i left semi-satisfied, freezing cold, and a burning hole in my pocket for what is supposed to be &quot;<span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>&quot; prices. the portions are super small, the food is meh, and of course, all largely overpriced. shrimp beignets were okay. mostly dough with bits of shrimp, if you could find any. lobster roll'boy was loaded with mayo and celery, almost like a tuna salad. i really wanted to like it, but i couldn't get over how much mayo they put. couldn't really taste the lobster. the pickled veggies that came with it, on the other hand, were a nice contrast.oysters on the half were super disappointing. 6 of the smallest oysters i've ever seen for $16? i'm such an oyster lover, but even the fanny bay oysters couldn't win me over.although there was a live jazz band playing, it was just too loud for anyone to socialize. scanning the room, it didn't seem like anyone was having fun, mostly because all you could do was sit there. granted that we came for late night <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> at 11 pm, it was a pretty chilly nite. but i just don't understand why they would leave all the windows open and still turn the ac on. the draft is a killer if you're not expecting it. after receiving the bill, me and my boyfriend were offered two mini-sized mason jars for free daquiri tasting at the bar before we left. my favorite was the mint julep - it was so refreshing and yummy.tl;dr - super small portions, overpriced, mediocre meal, could've gotten better food at a food truck...
preux &amp; proper is located right where spring and main converge (across from verve) and serves new orleans inspired cuisine. the dining room is very open and airy with windows on all sides and patio seating with a nice view of the cityscape. i ordered the fried chicken po'boy, which was easily one of the best chicken sandwiches i've ever had. the bread was soft, yet firm. the chicken was crispy and juicy. the condiments added a nice spicy kick. the sandwich came with a small side of chips. my friend ordered the salt roasted pork lion and was equally impressed. will definitely be back for the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>!
my new favorite <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>! 4-6pm, even on the weekends. the delicious food is almost half off and the drinks (not specialty cocktails) are buy one get one free. the bartenders and service staff are great as well. i've tried almost everything on the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> menu. the fried oyster po'boy, the smoked shrimp beignets, and the frog legs are a must! i thought the crab cake was just okay (but i'm a crab cake snob, no one can touch maryland crab cakes), but my friend enjoyed it. my friend also really liked the belly bites. the deviled eggs are also good. now for the wings, they were too small for my taste and the jerk flavor was aggressive, so i wouldn't order them again, since there are so many other dishes that i loved. the specialty cocktails are tasty, louisiana lemonade, yum! the frozen drinks are good but if you're looking to get a little buzz, it's not going to happen with those. the moonshine, yes moonshine, is worth a try but i'm much more interested in a tasty cocktail.i hope preux and proper makes it, unfortunately this corner seems to be cursed. it's been 3 different restaurants in less than 5 years. this one is my favorite!
i went two nights in a row, once for dinner to get a feel for the place, and then again to try <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. i saw the same friends of the bartender both nights. it made me reluctant to sit at the bar the next night.the first night the place was still packed from <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. there was a general air of merriment. you could hear people cheering through the open windows from the street like there was a game on. <span class="highlighted">happy</span> drunks who must have wanted jobs there both greeted us and wished us a good night when we left. upstairs it was the same vibe. there was some kind of event or party, because they were all taking pictures of each other and giving toasts. it is a good place for groups. the table configuration lends to it. there is a patio upstairs, and if no one is eating nearby, you can smoke and drink there. i saw a lot of folks getting the punch bowl of booze for 4.i didn't try any of the specialty cocktails, which were frankly boring. but i did have an excellent california chardonnay with my meal of a half dozen oysters, the steam pot and sides of cauliflower and greens.the west coast oysters from washington needed a lot of sauce. they tasted fine, but they didn't seem very fresh. the cauliflower was adequate, but still forgettable. i liked the greens with the steam pot. they were salty and spicy, reminding me of how my friend's mom on long island makes them to eat with the clams her dad would catch on the weekend.the steam pot we'll get into with the service, which could use some improvement. we sat down and a waitress came over. it seems they have a rehearsed spiel that they have been trained to deliver to you.she went through it, went away, and then another guy wandered over, introduced himself and launched into the same speech. the hostess came over and grabbed him like a first grade teacher in a pageant with the little boy who can't wait to deliver his line. he looked upset and embarrassed and was sulky the rest of the night when he ran food to our table.we asked the server what was in the steam pot. she said it had lobster, shrimp, crab and sausage. that sounded wonderful, but there was no lobster and no apology. there were two kinds of sausage (andouille and kielbasa) thrown in to make up for the missing lobster. our steam pot was three head on prawns, two little corn cobs, some potatoes and soup vegetables and a hunk of crab without the claw.when we declined dessert, she brought us two little jars and explained they were traditional lagniappes that we could take to the bartender downstairs to be filled with the frozen drink of our choice. i had the rum runner, and my husband had the rocket fuel. that was when we &quot;met&quot; the bartender's friends. they were there the next day right on the corner of the bar by the front door. the two seats between them and the door were the only ones left at the bar. we tried to run upstairs, but it was roped off. the bartender explained they don't open it until 6pm. it wasn't horrible, just awkward being forced by proximity into their conversation, shit-talking mutual acquaintances, and loudly i might add, or watching coverage of the boston marathon bombing on espn. it was definitely a less lively mood that day.they noticed the look of horror on my face and others' and changed the channel finally. &quot;how did that get on there?&quot; i mumbled, &quot;i guess it's sports.&quot;there are two <span class="highlighted">happy hours</span>, an early and a late one. only the early one has drink specials, dollar off beer and 2-for-1 well drinks, no cocktails. then there is a reduced price <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> food menu. we had the corn fritters with jalape&ntilde;o and the pork belly bites. i was hoping the corn fritters would be the brilliant love child of hush puppies and jalape&ntilde;o poppers, but they were just corn fritters. the menu description implied they could be more, especially with creme fraiche included. it must have been in the batter.the pork belly bites were good, nicely fried with a spicy maple sauce and served in lettuce leaves. i think <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> is going to be the ticket until they work out some kinks in the kitchen and service, and because the late <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> is from 11pm-1am, it's a good choice for a cheap late night bite before bed. cute date spot, too.
this place is just awesome, drinks, staff and food are all amazing. yesterday i ate the best big gourmet burger and with fresh big rustic hand made french fries i have had in awhile, all for just $12. who knew <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> is on here every sunday..... a gem thanks folks at p&amp;p. hope to return very soon.
ambience is so perfect! sit upstairs in the balcony and it's easy to imagine you aren't in la. we showed up for the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> from 11-1pm just on accident and ended up very surprised on the find. we had:- froglegs: one of the best in la. very moist, lightly pan fried and very well seasoned. with bits of their okra salad mixed in. - corn fritters: fried up balls of goodness- belly wraps: pork belly on lettuce. like candied bacon. - lobster roll: nice touch with the avocado and hot sauce on top. one of the best ones i've had. came with pickles that definitely tasted housemade. parking is pretty easy on the street (on a fri late night) and tables were available inside and out. service is prompt and attentive. not sure about the regular dinner menu prices, but i was quite <span class="highlighted">happy</span> with the whole experience. walking distance to golden gopher is a plus.
finally came here to try the food! short update:oyster po boy- the batter is a little lighter and thinner than the ones at new orleans, but it was a delicious sandwich. love the sauce that went with it!shrimp beignets- as yummy as they say. kind of like a shrimp pancake but deep fried. with the same awesome sauce. favorite dish of the night. steam pot- great light broth with corn and onions. also has sausages, andouille sausage, and shrimp. my friend's favorite part was the sausage. dip the toast in the soup, put the toppings on top, and you've got yourself a winner. frog legs- also the same light batter, very flavorful, a little tougher than regular meat but it is frog legs. yum.mnus one star for the service. the bartender didn't really know what he was doing, and put our order in wrong until we corrected him. the drunken watermelon punch he was unable to make accurately, and the other guy had to help him out. so much ice in the punch; it's supposed to server 4-6, but the two of us finished it no problem. we also couldn't order corn fritters because it wasn't <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> yet? not sure what he was saying but damn. i rather come for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>! the other bartender was super nice though, gave us samples on the drinks and whatnot. other than that, still a great new restaurant with a ton of potential!
recently came here last week for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> with my girlfriends &amp; i was excited because i had come for the first time the weekend before &amp; had a good time. seating: well this time around it was crowded of course because it was <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> but wish the seating was better. they have two levels downstairs they have a outdoor patio with a huge communal style eating table that was full when i came. they also have maybe two tables that fit four people also full that day and the other options are bar style tables for two, which was not the best for our party of five but we pulled some seats up &amp; toughed it out. drinks: they appear to have a nearly full bar, but me &amp; my friend came for the daiquiris. the first time i came they let us sample the daiquiris, as this place is new orleans themed... food, decor &amp; drinks. however, this time around this new bartender wasn't as friendly but i ended up getting the pi&ntilde;a colada. among that they have mint julep, mango margarita, rocket fuel &amp; some coffee chocolate one wasn't the best to me. beware of the rocket fuel like the bartender stated its like college in a cup. it has everclear which is also a nola known liquor similar to moonshine &amp; super potent. if you wanna have a good time though go for it but pace yourself. upstairs: after our drinks we wanted to explore upstairs &amp; get some food but was told it didn't open til 6 which was when <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> ended. odd if you come with a big group &amp; small bar style table &amp; chairs are not big enough to hold meals. we just drank our drinks &amp; headed up after 6pm. once upstairs i can say i was impressed it was a nice size, cool decor &amp; even had a fresh oyster ala carte section. food: the food was mediocre. my friends ordered fried oyster poboy, brisket poboy, shrimp beignets &amp; fried frog legs. they said their meals were just okay but the frog legs were pretty good taste like chicken lol. i got the steak &amp; fries but when my food arrived it looked more like slivers of meat precut on a bed of fries i wasn't impressed for $20 so i returned &amp; got the preux burger which was actually pretty good. service: the waiter who took our food order was nice, checked on us &amp; was <span class="highlighted">happy</span> to replace my order. my second order came out pretty slow but guess it to be expected. i would probably come back for drinks as i work downtown, but not a top pick. btw, it's downtown so find street parking or there is a lot for $8 across the street.
read all the reviews and chef john, my cuisine journal buddy can't resist southern cuisine and has a tender spot for n'awlins. &nbsp;everyone's gone by the crossroads of this place and thought many times, &quot;what the heck! &nbsp;that place looks great!&quot; and on a thursday a few months back, we went for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. &nbsp;as previous yelpers have said it's an interesting mix. &nbsp;first impression: &nbsp;big bar edged by round stools to the left with a &nbsp;friendly bartender that gives a big wave. &nbsp;to the right - hightops with stools and a darling patio beyond. &nbsp;we stood just inside getting our bearings. &nbsp;staff hustled past us as water rushes by big boulders. &nbsp; no hostess to seat. &nbsp;looked at the bartender - &nbsp;&quot;sure, seat yourselves anywhere.&quot; &nbsp; second impression: &nbsp;walked upstairs with a service dog in arms. &nbsp;8 pounds. while looking around and feeling amazingly like we were on the upper deck of a double decker bus in london and loving the outdoor open ambiance on a gorgeous la evening, the hostess hustled up to us and said. &quot;err...no, we can't have a service dog upstairs...they're only allowed downstairs.&quot; &nbsp;ouch. &nbsp;really? &nbsp;so preux &amp; proper's position is that if you have a service dog they not only get to dictate where you can and cannot be, but also limit your entire dining experience? third impression: &nbsp;trekked downstairs, debating whether to create a ruckus or not. best not to involve chef john; &nbsp;this is my fight, not his. &nbsp;now the bar area is packed. &nbsp;out to the patio under a lovely california twilight sky where there's an &nbsp;italian pensione style, long high top table with stools all around. &nbsp;<span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> in la loosens the guarded stance and refreshing cocktails make elbow to elbow positions definitely ok. &nbsp;young exec, great haircut and healthy tan looked up from his beer, &quot;oh, yeah, they're gone,&quot; and waved at the 2 open stools. &nbsp;&quot;you're lucky the waitress out here is good; &nbsp;she'll take care of you.&quot; &nbsp;good to know and we told him so.fourth impression: &nbsp;it really is quaint and right in the heart of downtown los angeles with big ficus trees on either side. &nbsp;traffic streaming past the patio on both sides was definitely slowing down. &nbsp;our heads swivelled tracking the waitress. &nbsp;&quot;coming up&quot; came the cheerful promise and the waitress that &quot;takes care of you&quot; zoomed by. the table &quot;server&quot;, we're assuming, cleaned up the mess, wiped the table, delivered menus and asked if we wanted some water; &nbsp;then confirmed our suspicions that service was a big question mark? &nbsp;patio food service meant - ordering at the bar. &quot;when do we pay?&quot; &nbsp;&quot;the bartender starts a credit card tab.&quot; &nbsp; ok. &nbsp;not what we expected. &nbsp;i would've fought a little harder to stay upstairs if i'd known what the segregation meant...but the damage was already done.fifth impression: &nbsp;the schussing waitress who really was only a cocktail waitress never came back. &nbsp;the server brought the apres <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> menus. &nbsp;we walked in at 5:50pm but with all the seating and service delays, it was now 6:15pm and we already missed the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> menu? who only has <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> till 6pm??? &nbsp;disappointed!! &nbsp;did the bosses of the <span class="highlighted">happy</span> campers that were knawing on bones and slurping down their last <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> slushy and fruity drinks know their crew had cut out from work early? &nbsp;c'mon preux &amp; proper!! &nbsp;sixth impression: &nbsp;the menu is large for a &quot;find a seat wherever&quot; joint. &nbsp;the shrimp beignets were definitely not beignets. &nbsp;they are fritters, tasty but not beignets. &nbsp;chef john liked the frog legs; lightly fried finished with &nbsp;a spicy sauce with kick; &nbsp;fresh oysters were pre-tobasscoed and lemoned which is not acceptable darn it!! &nbsp;let me lemon and spice my lovely little molluscs in the manner of my own liking...while anticipating the slurping and full bodied splash of the ocean's salty brine. for those yelpers who say that the food arrives before the table settings - er...another peculiarity of preux &amp; proper is you need to go fetch your own cutlery. &nbsp; the tableware wrapped in fresh and spiffy cloth napkins are right by the doorway to the patio. &nbsp; what else did we have? &nbsp;oh yes...lobster po'boy and the fried rice. &nbsp;the rolls were soft and grilled just so, filled with a tasty lobster melange; &nbsp;fried rice? &nbsp;why? &nbsp;especially when there's china town right around the corner...why attempt something that's just going to make you look bad? &nbsp;seventh impression: &nbsp;we ordered wine; &nbsp;sadly, it was oxidized and i sent it back. &nbsp;the bartender made a personal trip to the table with a fresh bottle and poured. &nbsp;wish i could remember his name...well built irish chap that is honest and loves what he does. &nbsp;tell you what, preux and proper - he's your clean up batter. saves the day so to speak when the food is tasty but not remarkable; &nbsp;the service is none existent and conditions are crowded. &nbsp;keep the bartender, i will return just because he knows how to schmooze with humor and class; &nbsp;makes a great drink and he knows how to keep 'em coming back for more.
