i'm a sucker for new orleans food. so if someone wants to cook the bayou's best in la (that's los angeles, not the postal abbreviation for louisiana), i'm going to want to try it whether it's the little jewel of new orleans convenience market in chinatown or preux and proper in the wedge-shaped, short-lived parish space.dropping in for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, we started with the vieux carre and sweet tea smash cocktails which were a bit flat. the food was anything but flat. the fried frog legs were meatier and less rubbery than most legs. it's impossible for frog to beat the best fried chicken, but these came very close. of course, there was some spicy heat, but it was at a friendly level. there was also the correct amount of heat in the po-boy with crunchy fried oysters. the sandwich was a bit skimpy on the number of oysters and the bread didn't need toasting because the oysters had plenty of texture, but it had a refined simplicity with the sliced tomatoes and arugula that hit the right marks. i wasn't a fan of the &quot;belly bites&quot; which were chinese lettuce wraps using diced pork belly.
i love trying different bars in la and preux and proper did not disappoint.the location of the place already is interesting as it is located within a fork in the road. i personally thought it added charm to the place and fit with it's new orleans/jazz inspired decor. the music played upbeat jazz with a lot of ray charles and the like.the upstairs had a private dining party so my friend and i just hung out at the bar downstairs, partaking in the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> deals while contemplating the balance of the lesser of the two evils. the golden state warriors or lebron. hahaha.*btw, now la will never hear the end of the warrior fans/bandwagoners taunts as they chant from basically, the entire northern half of california. i didn't know sacramento was considered the bay.... poor kings. lol.any hoot, the drinks were great and strong. the food was good. the company i found at the bar were amazing and we had a very civil time watching game 2. would i come here again? no doubt.
as a local, i was excited to see a new place open their doors that served food late. the concept is one of many popping up around the city (new orleans theme) and i think they used the space beautifully. i have been here twice and my favorite food options have got to be from the late night <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> menu from (11pm till close). the belly bites and fries were all great. from the dinner menu, i had the roasted chicken which was not that good. the kale is done perfectly. the service is great and kudos on offering small cups to patrons so that they can try the booze slushies downstairs. if they are looking for constructive criticism i would say to focus more on improving the quality of the dinner menu plates. for the price of many of the items, i felt the taste and quality was a little lacking.
i have walked by this building for years and wondered when someone would finally buy this place and turn it into something amazing. well, it finally happened! i came here for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> (3-6) on a thursday around 5 pm. the place wasn't super packed and we were able to get a two top table by the window. i love the design of this place, very open, breezy, great views with a romantic and relaxed ambiance. very new orleans style, just really pristine and clean to be an actual bourbon st. bar :). they have a nice patio upstairs and downstairs, with the upstairs patio opening at 6pm. the drink menu looked really great, but with a $12-14 dollar price tag, we decided to skip cocktails and stick with their decent selection of $5 beers. their <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> consists only of food (no drinks) with items ranging &nbsp;from $5-$8 dollars. we decided to split the shrimp beignets to start. they came out hot and crispy, 5-6 pieces, with a side of what i would describe as cajun tarter sauce. pretty tasty to munch on, but i would like to try another small plate next time. we then ordered the oyster po boy and the brisket dip. the oyster po boy was fried nicely, the bread was perfect and the veggies paired well. it was lacking acidity and salt, so i requested some lemon and salt, which really made the flavors pop. my fiance ordered the brisket sandwich, which he devoured but also needed to add salt too. overall, i am really looking forward to spending more time at this perfect location and further exploring their menu!
good vibes and a great place to go for drinks after work. plenty of parking lots all around the restaurant, which range from $5 to $10 (remember to bring cash!). our party of 4 had a reservation at 6:30 and a few of us arrived early and had some drinks and fries at the bar during their <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> (ends at 6). they have a garage-like type door that they leave open, so if you come during a cold night like i did bring a jacket as it can get really chilly! they also had a shuffleboard table so you can play that while you have drinks as well. by 6:10 we had all arrived so we headed upstairs (stairs are in the far back) and checked in at the cute little check-in table. we were seated right away and our extremely friendly and helpful server helped us place our orders. i believe he said he was from louisiana so he knew many of the new orleans based dishes very well. he described all the dishes as new orleans style with a los angeles twist. we ordered the andouille corn dog, gumbo fries, roasted marrow bones, and smoked shrimp beignets. the dishes are served family style so you order to share. my favorite dish of the night was the andouille corn dogs. it came with 4 decently sized corn dogs and fries with ketchup, mustard, and relish on the side. the sausages used in the corn dogs had a small kick of spice and the buns were perfectly crispy. the fries were great as well and had plenty of that southern cajun spice. the toasted marrow bone was okay (the bread that comes with it is delicious though!). i don't think i'm too big of a fan of marrow bone in general so i wasn't able to enjoy it too much. the gumbo fries somewhat reminded me of poutine fries with all its sauce and meat, but it was slightly bland. i'm unable to eat seafood so i can't say much about the shrimp beignets, but the rest of my party seemed to enjoy it and our server stated that it is their most popular dish.at the end of your meal they give you a small jar to take downstairs to the bar to get a free sample of any frozen daiquiri. the bartender was great in helping us choose our daiquiris. i would highly recommend dining here!
food is great. ambience is great... &nbsp;but the service here sucks. little service at all!my boyfriend and i came here during <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> on a saturday afternoon. we walked in to this cute new orleans style restaurant and it was not busy at all. saw the daiquiri bar and we were thinking &quot;oh okay cool place!&quot; we were ready to order our food! unfortunately.. about 15 min later, no server did not even come to our table to greet us and take our orders and drinks.. and we were just sitting there. we couldn't wait anymore longer so we just literally got up to the bar and told the bartender our order... how ridiculous! i thought this was a sit-down restaurant! we eventually got our food and the server finally attended to our needs. food was delicious, especially the shrimp beignets! anyways, quick summary: great food, but don't expect good service here.
nestled in between one of the busiest intersections in downtown la, preux &amp; proper is a surprisingly peaceful restaurant. located across the street from lauded verve coffee, perfect for all us coffee addicts. we came here for their dinela <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> week - $4 beers!! $3 oyster shooters! $16 lobster roll! the outdoor patio is beautiful! service was quick, and attentive- i give them 4 stars! oyster shooters were nothing to rave about, though they were large, i thought they lacked flavor - 2 stars. the cajun ketchup really took the kennebec thick cut fries up a level - 4 stars! the beer was a bit warm for our liking considering it was 4:30pm and still 77 degrees out - 2 stars. my only gripe about this place has more to do with location than anything else - flies were all over the outdoor patio (though not when we moved indoors and probably because of the heat and weather) and finding metered parking would be nothing short of a miracle. expect to pay between $5 and $10 at the plentiful nearby surrounding lots!
in dtla, great tapas and cocktails place. &nbsp;definitely not for a large group but intimate 4-6 people at most! &nbsp;i think i'd prefer it as a date spot or a girls night place. &nbsp;overall loving the place and vibe.ambiance: imagine new orleans but mixed with hipster dtla. &nbsp;i love the open air feeling with all the windows and the upstairs/downstairs. &nbsp;it's a bit of a smaller place though so there may be a wait if you come during dinner time.food: hit or miss but overall thought it was an interesting take on new orleans tapas.frog legs: salty but not badpork belly hash: heavy but good. &nbsp;pork belly and poached egg, you get a lot of creaminess and then potatoes. &nbsp;definitely share this.lobster po boy: i liked it but i have had better. &nbsp;chunks of lobster were a bit small.muffalata board: fun take on the deconstructed muffalata.oyster po boy: not bad, fried oyster was good.gumbo fried rice: lack-luster. &nbsp;not bad/not goodfresh oysters: can't go wrong!drinks: instagram worthy cocktails!the westside: yummy and not too sweetblackberry honey sour: love the taste of the blackberry, also was not too sweetservice: awesome. &nbsp;they were so attentive and i'm not sure if it was the owner, but he kept coming over to talk to us and make recommendations. &nbsp;we even got 2 tapas on the house!price: we spent $30+ a person for tapas and drinksparking: lots everywhere. &nbsp;when in doubt, park across the street though it is $10.tip:<span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> 4-6
i've been to preux &amp; proper twice in the last month, and it's now on my list of low-key favorites for a sit-down meal downtown. it's a vibrant restaurant in the old parish space, with an upstairs dining room and a downstairs area with a bar, a patio, a shuffleboard table, and some smaller tables. the menu is new orleans fare, with cajun classics and a half dozen frozen daiquiris. the atmosphere is accordingly fun and festive.i first came on a tuesday night for a late, late dinner after the taping of the rupaul's drag race finale at the orpheum. this was the only restaurant within walking distance that was still open after midnight, and we were <span class="highlighted">happy</span> to find that not only was the kitchen still cooking, we'd also stumbled into <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> (4 to 6 and 11 to 1, maybe every day?). we ordered at the bar, set up camp on the patio, and had a great time. service got a little tangled, but the result was that we got an order of corn fritters no one in the restaurant had ordered. it would've been nice if we'd been told some of the sandwiches came with fries, as we ordered a couple superfluous sides of these we might not have gotten had we known. we put them to good use, though, and otherwise, service was great. the guy who helped us was really pleasant. also, there was this amazing musician singing on the piano--not sure where they got him, but he's a winner.when my friends and i needed a last minute saturday night downtown dinner spot a week later, i immediately thought of preux &amp; proper and was able to snag an online reservation with zero difficulty. this time we ate upstairs, and the space was neat, not crowded but comfortably busy, with a lively atmosphere. service was slightly more formal during regular dinner <span class="highlighted">hours</span>, and our waitress was great.it would be a mistake to come here and not have a drink, and i'd recommend going for it with a punch bowl or a frozen daiquiri. the punch bowls are $45, and they're just large format versions of some of the cocktails, holding around four or five drinks. the cocktails are $13 apiece, so think of sharing a punch bowl as a more colorful version of splitting a table bottle of wine. the punch bowls are supposedly good for 4-6 people, but we split one three ways and that seemed right. we got the blackberry honey sour, which combined buffalo trace bourbon, lemon, honey syrup, and blackberries. it wasn't perfect, but it tasted reasonably good. it was definitely strong. i haven't tried the other fancy cocktails, but i've sampled several of the daiquiris. i got one on my first visit, and we all got sample cups with our dinner check, so we could try some on our way out the door. (this was actually a great way to cap off dinner, as we didn't get dessert.) there are six daiquiri flavors and i've now tried the mango margarita, the call a cab, and the mint julep. they're all pretty simple, satisfying, slushy, sweet, and sufficiently boozy. the mango margarita is just tequila, mango, and margarita mix; the call a cab is strawberry and rum; the mint julep rye, mint, and simple syrup, probably the least juicelike daiquiri on offer.the food is also great. i've liked everything i've ordered. off the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> menu (which is also available for dinner), i'd strongly recommend the smoked shrimp beignets, the corn fritters, the proper fries, and the brisket dip. the shrimp beignets are delicious, hefty shrimp-studded balls of fried dough served with sea salt and remoulade. they're sweet, savory, and smoked, with excellent texture. the corn fritters are similar in function but not repetitive. they're wonderful little fritters bursting with corn, served with charred jalape&ntilde;o and creme fraiche. preux &amp; proper must just be good at frying things because the proper fries are some of my favorite french fries in l.a. they're wedge cut russet fries, crispy on the outside, creamy on the inside. the seasoning is on point, and they come with a spicy cajun catsup. for a <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> meal, that brisket dip is pretty clutch. it's a meaty sandwich served on a thick roll with plenty of brisket, hot mustard, house pickles, bacon jam, and jus.i tried a few fancier small plates type dishes at dinner, and these were also successful. my oyster shooter was fresh and piquant, with a kumamoto oyster, some spicy sauce, and a pickly diced garnish. if the brussels sprout appetizer is on special, i'd definitely recommend this one to share. charred brussels, pulled pork belly, orange slices, fresno chiles, and peanuts--pretty ideal. for a light entree, the grilled shrimp works very well. it feels like a riff on the barbecue shrimp i've had in new orleans. heads on, succulent, in a sauce loaded with garlic and butter. they come with these cubes of starchy potato that don't quite do it for me, but i guess the dish would be too small without them.my friends and i have been pleased with preux &amp; proper. it's low hassle and fun, with good food and drink at a manageable price point. i'm <span class="highlighted">happy</span> to have it as a new go-to spot.
located right at the fork that separates spring and main. it's noticeably long and narrow but you'll notice the space is used well. despite the narrow structure of this place it is surprisingly roomy. the interior is elegant but remains casual, making it a fit place to drop in for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> or even a date night dinner. preux &amp; proper is a southern themed restaurant, more of a new orleans type fixture. i have to admit, it feels more like an la archetype, but it has just enough southern charm to help you imagine that you're sitting on the patio of a new orleans garden district home. my review is solely based on the cocktails, as that was the only purpose for our visit. i imagined they would serve n'awlins classics, sazerac and vieux carr&eacute;, given the southern concept. sure enough they were on the menu, so that's an assured positive - and that's the poison we had to go with. but make no mistakes about it, the cocktail list also offers other drinks for those that prefer a fruity touch in their libation. the drinks were exceptional, giving me the impression that the bartender definitely knew what he was doing. we enjoyed our drinks and an order of cajun fries by the window-side seating overlooking spring. the view wasn't the most impressionable but the ambience was right, with jazzy tunes playing in the background. the staff and bartender were all welcoming hosts, so they've got the hospitality down. overall, i felt it was an enjoyable experience. i'm likely to come back in the future.
i am always excited to try new things such as this new orleans styled bar and diner located in the middle of downtown/short walk from pershing square. came here for a thirsty thursday get together. preux and proper look like a two story townhouse from the outside. there is an extended patio for the ground floor with several long benches combined together to create a commune kind of seating.since we had a large group (around 10 people), we sat at the long benches. it was a bit cold at night so it would have been nice to have some heating lamps like the second floor balcony. instead, we made do with our various jackets.there are a variety of drinks on the menu. most of us got the daiquiris which were $10. you can add an extra shot for $3. there are lots of different flavors. i tried the mango and the strawberry. both were extremely sweet. in fact, the mango didn't even taste like mango much. there were other cocktails and they serve a variety of flavored moonshine. during <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, which starts at 11 pm, certain appetizers are a few dollars off. we got the frog legs, french fries, and shrimp beignets. the food was average at best. perhaps the actual meal items taste better, but since we were drinking, we ordered bar food. the food were all a bit heavy on spices, which overwhelmed much of the food items.service was attentive to everything. nice place to visit but i'm not sure if i will come back at night because a lot of hobos came to the patio to beg. it was a bit of a shock to see several people pop out of the semi-bushes. the security did their best to dissuade them from appearing, but it definitely serves as a dark reminder of the ever growing homeless population in the area. if you do see them, please offer them food as we wanted to do.
dinela <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> week - come at me.parking: street or nearby lot. bring cash just in case as most of them are cash only.food:seafood boil: mm the huge lobster pieces were my favorite! this thing was loaded with shellfish - i would say it's good enough to split between two people if you want a significant portion. broth was light but flavorful.corn fitters - i would pass on these as they taste as if they're made from the same batter as the shrimp beignets. definitely not enough corn.shrimp beignets - i thought this would rock my world, but it was just good. i had a really nice bite of shrimp, but there isn't a large enough portion of it to deem it a shrimp beignet..more of a beignet with shrimp.deviled eggs - if you like guacamole, you'll love this. loved the bacon bits, but i'm not a fan of avocado so i'll pass on this next time.fried oyster po boy - loved that this had arugula to balance out the flavor of the oyster. bread was decent, but the filling to bread ratio was too low for my liking.fries- they taste like they've been twice fried - exactly the way i like them! drink:sweet tea punchbowl- dang this thing was strong. maybe i'm super basic, but i love the idea of a huge communal punch bowl. i would say this is definitely worth the money as 4 of us struggled to finish it. great for large groups!service: our waiter was very attentive and charismatic. he checked on us occasionally and kept our water glasses full (and my boyfriend drinks a lot of water). atmosphere:p&amp;p is definitely one of those new generation of downtown restaurants - bar/restaurant/hang out. the first floor is standing room only while upstairs houses the restaurant. on the friday that we went, there was a live jazz band! pretty cool. i'd definitely come back on a warm summer night :) don't forget your complimentary daquiris on your way out!
