preux and proper has long been on my list of bookmarks and after reviewing the menu it offered for dinela i decided it would be the perfect time to check it out. my friend and i met here after work at around 6pm and to my surprise the restaurant was a tall and narrow building that was part of an island separating two opposing streets of traffic in downtown la. the first word that came to mind upon entering the restaurant was airy. it was full of large, open windows and felt incredibly close to the street. it is the opposite of intimate as it was very bright with natural light coming from all the windows but it was still very welcoming. louis armstrong was playing in the background and though no one greeted me in the downstairs bar area the atmosphere still gave me an inviting feeling. as we waited for our upstairs dinner table, my friend and i perused the drink menu at the downstairs bar. we noticed a row of cocktail slushies that looked like a fancier version of those you might see at 7/11. we couldn't exactly decide which we wanted or if we wanted one at all so the bartender allowed us to sample each one in small mason jars. my friend and i each had our favorites. she really enjoyed the pina colada mixed with the banana fosters while i enjoyed the strawberry mixed with the mango margarita. a flight of these sweet, alcoholic sampler slushies was just the refresher we needed before heading upstairs for dinner. upstairs there are two and four-person tables near the open windows that allow you to have a great view of downtown while enjoying your meal. it also has another bar in addition to the one downstairs. as soon as we walked up the stairs we were warmly greeted by two hosts who sat us immediately. our server was very welcoming and polite, explained the dinela menu and advised what his favorite drinks were. my friend had the old fashioned and i had the hibiscus drink that our server recommended. my drink was very floral and refreshing and didn't dilute as the ice was arranged like an iceberg with the majority of it sticking out of the glass. i started with the chips and dips: soy bean hummus and voodoo chips. the taste of the hummus was very subtle and fortunately was balanced out with the flavor of the bbq chips that accompanied it. i then had the smoked shrimp beignets. they were definitely my favorite part of the meal. the breading and shrimp were warm and soft and didn't taste overly fried. the shrimp flavor wasn't underwhelming and tasted great with the tartar sauce. finally i had the crab etouffee. the crab was spiced up with a cajun flavor of sorts and really helped the more subtle flavor of the grits. my friend had the grits on their own and they really needed an accompaniment as they were a bit too bland to stand on their own. i loved the music, service, atmosphere and interior at preux and proper. it's really hard not to have a great time when you have an amazing view of the surrounding area with relaxing music playing in the background. however, i wasn't quite impressed with the food or the portions and am glad that i got to experience this place during restaurant week when i was able to try a few different dishes and get an overall feel for their meals. i would still definitely return for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> to have another one of those slushies and wind down on the patio. this place is truly unique with the atmosphere it provides and is worth a visit.
