atmosphere:if you're looking for this place, and feel like you've made a wrong turn, are in the wrong neighborhood, or are seeing endless rows of empty streets and warehouses, keep going. you're on the right track. this small brick building looks like it was just dropped onto the corner of a vacant parking lot and haphazardly wrapped with a tall tarped fence. to make a &quot;patio environment&quot; on the inside. however odd it looks from the outside, objective achieved. i felt transported to the 1920's when i walked through the entrance and was faced with a tall glass window fa&ccedil;ade lined with different colored bottles like an apothecary would have in their storefront. inside, the wood bar, old pictures mounted on the wall, cash register, every little detail was in theme. it was fantastic. food:great, large veggie burger with a generous amount of &nbsp;addicting fries get the fried chickpeas appetizer. drinks:no wine.. saaaad face.plenty beer options on tap.&quot;libations&quot; are not &quot;calorie-friendly&quot; (yeah. i said it. sue me) but are very interesting looking and tasting. $12 for most..belladonna - not my favorite. muddled blackberries just piled on top of crushed ice with hard liquor and mint at the bottom of the mason jar. (not as tasty as it sounds)overall: the bartender wasn't the most helpful when i was trying to determine what drink to buy (i usually just drink wine!). he wasn't mean but he didn't seem to have much patience for the novice hard-alcohol drinker. the patio was a nice place to sit. not cold at all.. there were plenty of people from <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> (time.. there is no <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> menu fyi) until late into the night. overall fun place to try in downtown. just don't drive there alone..
