came here on a sunday afternoon around 5 pm for a friend's birthday. this is an odd place.the best part is the bar. rows and rows of colored-glass bottles lit up from behind make an impressive backdrop to the bar, and it's really cool that it's in this little tucked-away room. the bartenders are really competent; they really know what they're doing as they mix it up! also, sunday's <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> prices are pretty awesome! i had the most delicious cocktail called a bella donna; it was like a vodka snow cone! super tasty! the bf got a huge mason jar of noble pilsner beer for about the same price.the strange part is the rest of the venue. it's like a circus tent set up on the asphalt of a parking lot, and there are tables and chairs inside the tent, but it was really dark in there. no lights at all. we had to go sit outside on the small patio for a moment to get out of that claustrophobic tent. even outside it was really dark. i couldn't see my friends' faces even when they were sitting right in front of me. finally after an <span class="highlighted">hour</span> of this, an employee turned on the patio lights. the grateful crowd clapped and cheered. also, it's cool that the bar is separate but the cocktail mixing requires time, so the line quickly built up and the small bar room grew congested with a throng of people. the line became so long that i completely gave up trying to order a second drink. it wasn't worth it to stand in that line.we stayed because it was a friend's birthday, but only for that reason.
i was excited to finally visit the spot and loved it upon arrival - there's a big free parking lot that leads right into the double-wide doors, which lead right into the heart of the bar, which sits in front of this amazing wooden mirror art. from the bar looking out, there are hundreds of colored glass bottles sitting on shelves along the large glass windows, filtering the light in their rainbow colors. there's seating inside and outside and best of all, upstairs. this is where the wild west comes in - sitting upstairs, i felt like i was in an old western shanty-town keeping tabs on all the locals. very cool.besides the $3 schlitz, villains also offers $3 bud lights &amp; tecates (which they had run out of). on top of that, they've got a wide selection of draft beers served in glass mugs for $6 - add a shot and it's only $8. for a medium-sized draft beer + shot, it's $10 and for a large w/shot, it's $16. prices go up for premium &amp; super premium drinks.not as budget friendly are the $10 wines by the glass, the $12-13 specialty drinks, and sadly, the awesome $9 sno-cone fix that villains is known for. pick any fruit and any spirit and they'll make you up a delicious grown-up sno-cone treat; i don't think i've had a better cocktail in recent days than the fantastic strawberry &amp; rum concoction i ordered. booze got lemon &amp; vodka, which was all right, but man, mine was better :).as we had dinner plans to visit wurstk&uuml;che just a few blocks away, we forwent the dining experience at villains, though i definitely plan to sample some vittles next time i visit. in the past, my <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> tour partner has tried the grilled cheese with bacon marmalade and loved how crispy the sandwich was. some other exciting <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>-y food options include fire roasted corn on the cob ($4), bourbon bacon caramel corn ($5), wicked fries w/ parmesan &amp; parsley ($6), and indian peas - deep fried chick peas dusted with chili-lemon sea salt ($5). dios mio, i'm salivating just thinking about my next visit!!
