i'll start with the good: &nbsp;loved the decor of the place and seems like a cool place to hang out and get drinks. &nbsp;but here's the bad: &nbsp;rude female bartender that didn't know how to make drinks. &nbsp;we ordered a drink off of their specialty cocktail list ($13), it was a lavendar blueberry something and at first she hesitated because she wasn't sure if they had all the ingredients, then after checking she confirmed that she did have the ingredients. &nbsp;then she proceeded to make the drink but kept referring to the menu to check the ingredients. &nbsp;we also ordered a few other drinks for my group of 7 people. &nbsp;i tasted my specialty cocktail and it definitely wasn't what i imagined, but i thought maybe it's an acquired taste. &nbsp;i had my friends try it and they all exclaimed it was disgusting and to return it. &nbsp;we went to the bar to return the drink and she gave us a hard time! &nbsp;finally she relented and said she would do it this time. &nbsp;i asked for a simple gin and tonic in return and she just gave me well gin and a very small pour, didn't even fill the jigger up. &nbsp;i would think that being a bartender she should at least know how to make the specialty drinks and if not be nice about it and offer a replacement without being a bitch. we had also ordered a red wine for my friend and it was stale, but after the poor experience with the bartender we didn't bother trying to complain. &nbsp;i may try this place again, but not unless it's <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> because the drinks definitely weren't worth the high price.
when i first heard from my friend that drinks come in mason jars, i wanted to check it out. what novelty! &nbsp;drinks come in three sizes of mason jars: small, medium, or large. apparently they are all obtained from different places, so i'm assuming they were mostly donated.i came during <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> on a saturday, so there was no crowd. cocktails were about $1-2 off, and i think the mix &amp; match drinks (beer + a shot) were half off. they didn't have a very exotic selection for these, just very basic beers and shots. they do have some interesting signature cocktails, but because i was dd, i didn't get a drink. i really wanted to try the inigo montoya though (&quot;you killed my father. prepare to die!&quot;)the ambience was very interesting. the whole place reminded me of a saloon that you would find in western movies, except it looks more like a cross section of a house with a yard on its side. there's a small second floor where i would assume shady business is conducted because of how dark it is, and the first floor has a large open area under a tent where there are more tables (this is the yard). the neighborhood can seem pretty shady, especially at night. there's nothing around the bar except for factories, but it does have its own parking lot.
came to villains tavern for a special event sponsored by &quot;this is not a pop-up&quot; which specializes in getting leading edge chefs around southern california to cook for a short length of time to show off their culinary skills &amp; imagination. &nbsp;the theme of the ayce was louisiana crawfish boil with sides such as sweet corn bread, dirty rice, grits with sauteed mushrooms, red beans with pork belly, french fries with cajun seasoning. &nbsp;the boiled crawfish &amp; sweet corn boil in the spice mix were great....very close to what you would find in west feliciana parrish in southern louisiana. &nbsp;the louisiana style crawfish boil spice mix is full of powdered spicy hot red chiles, garlic, probably allspice, cloves, cinnamon,etc which creates a complex, totally satisfying complement to the crawfish as well as accentuating the contrast of the sweet, fresh corn to the heat of the chiles. &nbsp;mexicans, i'm sure, can relate to this by &nbsp;sprinkling on dried chile powder called &quot;pico de gallo&quot; on their boiled corn cob.to pair with this feast, i decided to get a truly exotic concoction which i saw previously being made for another customer. &nbsp;the drink, i found out, was named after loki, the god of mischief in the pantheon of germanic/nordic gods. &nbsp;loki was a trouble maker and could sometimes fool even odin/wodin, the king of the gods, into doing something that could adversely affect mortals as well as the gods.loki was a mixture of various infusions such as honey peach, various citrus flavours, liquers, angostura bitters as a finishing touch. &nbsp;of course, the bartender was rather vague about the ingredients since some of these cocktails are proprietary secrets of the house. &nbsp;the bar-t put a snow come of crushed ice so it looked like a cold volcano &amp; added more angostura bitters as a coloring on top. &nbsp;he garnished with a single grey-green leaf of sage. &nbsp;loki was more like an herbal, citrus fruit driven tonic with sweet bitterness. it is certainly a thirst quencher for a hot summer, early fall afternoon. to top it off, it was <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> prices so i got $2 taken off so that it cost $11. &nbsp;not cheap, but with all the work needed to make the infusions, the price was justified. &nbsp;it was perfect in putting out the heat of the chiles in the louisiana spice mix, and it was a good palate cleanser between bites of the spicy cajun/creole louisiana cuisine. &nbsp;the mood at villains tavern is noir, lugubrious, brooding even on a bright afternoon, warm sunny day. &nbsp;in the dead of night, it would seem to be the ideal venue for the nosferatu's, vampires, &amp; the undead to congregate into the wee <span class="highlighted">hours</span> of the dark, dark night. &nbsp;be sure to wear a garland of garlic around your neck &amp; carry a gun with only silver bullets, and &nbsp;that may still not be enough.
i gotta claim hipster discrimination at this place. i live in silver lake but this downtown arts district gives up nothing to the sl when it comes to curly mustachios and men in tight fitting clothing. came with a fellow non hipster. let's just call him cal. cal is white, from iowa and likes to wear baseball caps. we had just come from golfing at the los feliz par three so i was dressed in some jcrew and plaid shorts -- hipster strike #1....cal's hat said ucla. cal was told to take off hat by bouncer in long locks that was reading some poetry because he probably visited city lights bookstore once or twice when in san francisco. even though fashionista male hipsters hoping to become the next steve madden were parading around in knock off ed hardy type hats with the bill straight... sports hat = hipster strike #2... bouncer said it was czu people get &quot;mad crazy about their team.&quot; cal points out there is no tv in bar as hipsters hate sports because they got picked last in gym class...we are then told they don't have full menu at the moment. only option is basically pulled pork and chip/fries... we came cause yelp said they have burger and its a gastro pub.bartender can't figure out how to get me side of mayo even though pulled pork came with it... finally after 2 trips back to kitchen i am told i have have a side of mayo. hipster in service industry actually had to do their job for the expected 25% tip = hipster strike #3. in all fairness i thought the pulled pork was decent but it was smothered in this spicy mayo that may have masked the taste. chips were cold and soggy... mayo was the best thing about the place. cal doesn't get hipster mayo so he had his plain and said it was dry and tasteless.on way out some guys in baggy hoodies and la dodger hats left. we pointed out to bouncer the dodger are also a sports team. bouncer said they know the chef... apparently you need a chef to serve one sandwich and fries. we asked bouncer if he was aware of the aclu. bouncer said he's never heard of them. should also point out bouncer is african america. cal tells bouncer he should put down the bukowski and pick up some malcolm x. we leave never to return. prosthe beers are ok is diverse selection but way overpriced for where they are in location. $10+ unless you get a <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> special like heiny light for $1 which saved the experience for us. conseverything else. too many hipsters. service with attitude and not a full menu on a saturday afternoon.
went here thursday for a <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> after work.pretty difficult to find and once you do find it, you'd wish it wasn't in this neighborhood.they have parking but their &quot;lot&quot; was full at 6 due to no marked parking spaces and people parking haphazardly with no regard to others.once you get inside the bar has a pretty good feel and neat decor. plenty of outside seating with propane heaters and a cozy upstairs seating area.it is a neat concept with mix and match beer and shot combination for pretty good prices. good selection of beer and liquor so no complaints there.my biggest complaint thought is the inordinate amount of time it takes the bar tenders to make their &quot;specials&quot;. each drink consists of no less than 10 separate steps and each is completed with a different type of liquor that is at opposite ends of the bar from each other.it's a neat concept that the bar takes time to craft these special drinks but the amount of time to complete these tasks is unacceptable.i needed a drink so i head to the bar (no waiters or waitresses) and thankfully only a party of two people waiting in line ahead of me. i honestly waited more that three songs playing on the radio before the bartender completed one of their drinks, tested it through a straw, dumped it out and started over.i appreciate their concern for quality control but this situation needs to be remedied. there were three bartenders at the beginning of my venture to get a drink and during this time, the line grew in extreme proportions.at one point, while there were ten people in line, one of the bartenders (who appeared to be a shift manager) stopped making drinks, pulled out his cellphone, and proceeded to converse with a patron and then headed upstairs without looking at the line of potential customers.luckily for me, the gentleman behind me in line was talkative and we started up a small conversation. one of my friends joined us after a bit because they came looking for me thinking that i had left after being gone for such a long time.the interesting thing was that i had ordered a burger earlier in the evening and was one of the best i've had in awhile. fries were a little overcooked but the burger was delicious with cheese, bacon, and some sort of cranberry chutney on it. the elapsed time from ordering the burger to receiving it at my table was less than the time it took me to order one beer at the bar with a line of two people and three bartenders.so, overall, this place has extreme potential. cool motif, good food, and good drinks. however, since they are a new establishment, i would recommend waiting a few months for management to train their bar tenders, figure out how to stripe a parking lot, and attach the granite tabletops to the table bases (watch out for loose table tops inside).
