pour haus is in a cute little one block stretch in the industrial area about a half a block away from church and state. there's not a lot of street parking so park in the parking lot across the street, it costs $10. don't try to find street parking more than a block away because the neighborhood gets a little dodgy. you will be poured a glass of lambrusco right when you walk in and brought a bowl of popcorn. there's only a few spots outside, and about eight tables inside. we went on a sunday afternoon at 3:00 and there were plenty of places to sit. this was right in the middle of <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> where they've got great specials. glasses of wine and small plates for $5. you can also do a wine tasting of three different lines for about $12 or you can buy a bottle for anywhere from $24 for the lambrusco up to $80 for higher end wines. we ordered the bruschetta and added on the additional burrata cheese and the greek nachos. both were delicious but if we had to pick one we both would've chosen the bruschetta. the staff was super friendly the ambience was relaxing we would definitely come back
a big group of us went here for a friend's birthday brunch last year. the place is cute, not very big, but they were able to seat us all inside at some high tables. they have a large selection of games to play, so we enjoyed a couple games of cards against humanity. those were the positive points. i don't know how their dinner menu is, but avoid the brunch here. they do offer bottomless mimosas, but we discovered that they were very watered down. this wasn't just conjecture; one of our group who got there first ordered a mimosa, but they misunderstood and didn't realize he was planning to do the bottomless deal. his mimosa was significantly better than what we were served for our entire meal. put it another way: we ate and drank from about noon until 5ish, and none of us had more than the slightest buzz. fail. the food also ranged from mediocre to just terrible. a couple of us ordered the tortilla soup, and it must have been the worst tortilla soup i have ever had. there was almost nothing in it! chicken? that's a joke. they hardly even added tortilla strips. the mac-n-cheese was paste-y and lacked flavor. the croque monsieur was just average. the only thing that saved this meal was our fun group of friends. the games helped distract us from the &quot;meh&quot; food and drink. i've been back once since then, when friends chose it as a meeting point for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. i guess the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> isn't that bad, but there are so many better options in la.
