a few travel blogger friends and i decided to meet-up at this place. i love this place! great wide selection of wine!! pour haus is in the arts district in dtla the place is difficult to find as it is tucked away in the very small street on industrial street. after making a few turn arounds i finally found the place. i found parking at the street as it was early enough. at night though there is a paid parking lot you can park at. we went on a saturday during their <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. wine and appetizers for half off- great deal! lots of food selection but i would have to admit the food was a-ok ( -1 star for that) but a few are good for vegans and vegetarians and light-eaters. other than that the wine selection is great!the crowd is as diverse as it can be. artsy, hipster looking, and older crowd, diverse is best! our waiter was awesome! so friendly and took care of us. a++ for customer service. i have been recommending this place to the rest of my friends.
while the receipt still says swill automatic, this place is definitely a new wine and beer joint in the arts district. as i scoured for parking on a tuesday at 6:00 p.m., i found that the best option was to pay to park. i thoroughly enjoyed giving my car to a valet who then moved it 30 feet into a slot for me. parking gods 1, me 0.seeing as how many people seem to really like this place, i will highlight what i was critical about during the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> visit. what i found slightly concerning, to begin with, were the prices. while the arts district boasts a very kitchy and higher-than-average food scene, i felt like pour haus could have been more competitive. they have plenty of wines and a decent beer selection at good prices, but i feel like their price to quantity ratio is off. i suppose we should have figured out how hungry we were, and how large the portions were. either way, we had to order more and paid a little bit more than expected.greek nachos: while i saw these as a hot mess, they were actually quite stuffing. the nachos were basically toasted flat bread with lots of yogurt oozing off the sides like ninja turtle slime. i recommend this for those who want to fuel up.the mix n' match standard: i am not sure if i really liked this platter, as it seems to be the thing people order while sipping on wine, yet it's not really a filler-upper. it's a great conversational group of items that you can snack on without looking like a slob, but you'll probably be disappointed with the lack of taste in cheese, jams, and olives. this is only worth it if you're trying to impress someone, or coming here to snack.stuffed mushrooms: very much like stuffed eggplant, you'll note these will go quick. they are, however, oily.oxtail taco: probably my favorite dish in the whole place. now this is food, and i'm <span class="highlighted">happy</span> i found it here. the beef will fall apart as you try to eat it, and it will ooze with flavor as you bite into it. consider wearing a bib or black shirt. or just eat it in a corner.while i suppose the dishes are best for 2-3 people or that individual plates may be the way to go during <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, i would hope that their beer selection increases the next time around to more than what has now become traditional ipa and light (stone, stella, racer 5, etc.). although i am not sure about their wines, i can recommend that you certainly try the oxtail tacos above all other things, and take your time to park. you may also want to note that the noise level may be higher on weekends, but for a tuesday night it was great. i hope to be back here again, with better knowledge as to what to order so as to get the most out of my experience.
