pour haus wine bar is located in downtown la. it was rated &quot;best downtown <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>&quot; by la weekly. they pride themselves in fine wine, craft beer, and gourmet food. the moment we entered we were greeted immediately. then another server asked to check our ids. she seemed rather stern at first but later on grew to be friendly. their menu is mainly of a tapas style cuisine ranging from french, spanish, and meditteranean that changes throughout the year. interesting subheadings on the menu including noshes, snacks n stuff, the precursors, the substantial, and the finale. their happiest <span class="highlighted">hour</span> menu is only $5 per dish. choices on their happiest <span class="highlighted">hour</span> menu include bruschetta, oxtail tacos, greek nachos, pizza, veggie grill, papitas bravas, noshes, dips &amp; pita, grilled cheese and soup, and bowl of mixed berries. they also have lunch specials and a brunch menu.their wine menu has a pretty good selection including flights of the month, rhone varietals, and bordeaux varietals to name a few. our server started us off with a sparking red wine from the happiest <span class="highlighted">hour</span> menu. popcorn was also served on the table. i also tried a red wine which was rather smooth with some tannins. later on, i had a sauvignon blanc which was slightly acidic and sweet. we ordered some food from the happiest <span class="highlighted">hour</span> menu. the oxtail tacos were okay, even though they were meaty it was still lacking a bit of flavor. the mac n cheese was good although it could have a bit more cheese flavor. the dips and pita were also good, i liked the red pepper feta dip the most as it had a little spice to it. all the dishes arrived rather promptly.they also have a great selection of games on the shelves. this includes cranium, connect 4, trouble, checkers, cards against humanity, scrabble, mastermind, risk, and many more. we ended up playing cards against humanity. i won the game because apparently i happen to chose the best cards. parking can be a bit difficult to find. there's not much available unless you're able to park across the street or the streets around the area.overall, i had a great time here. food was decent but the wine and service was pretty good. plus, the games available made it fun too. recommended to go for the wine and games! i'll be back for another visit.
i might have given 41/2 stars, but it leans more to 5 then 4, so there ya go.  this place is reasonably priced and has a good selection of wine(you can purchase it too!). i love the truffle popcorn, whoever complained about it being stale....it is tossed with truffle oil, so no it probably wouldn't be crunchy, but hey...it's free and quite tasty. i love that i can buy a pretty good bottle of wine for less then $25 bucks! and you get a free tast when you first sit down!  really enjoyed the charcuterie and cheese platter and the zucchini/squash salad. the mac and cheese is hit or miss, great flavor but occasionally not thick enough. riblets are good, always tender. hummus dips are yummy. and we aways get the smores to finish up our meal. the menu definitely plays to a more shared or tapas style.  terrific beer selection, it changes a lot. and their <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> is fantastic! i think there is a dj on the weekends.trivia too! don't recall the night it is, but it's a fun crowd.
i really just wanted to see what all the five-star fuss was about. i enjoy the softer side of the drinking scene: &nbsp;small, quiet, low lit, romantic places where you can actually go and enjoy the company of the person you're with. &nbsp;that is le pour haus. &nbsp;located on a one-way street in the middle of industrial downtown los angeles outskirts, the tiny wine bar is just perfect: for dates, for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, for a light snack, to enjoy the flights, to banter with the friendly wait staff.the menu is pretty impressive, and i liked that if you chose a wine that was for sale (yes they have bottles of wine lining the walls that you can pick from), they would un cork it for you and you have the option of taking the entire bottle home with you. there were three flights to choose from, i picked the $10.00 australian flight:taltarini lalla gully reisling (white)hesketh &quot;usual suspects&quot; shiraz (red)killakoon killerman's run sauvignon (red)for snacks we had:peppadew pepper poppers: stuffed with goat cheese and chives, prosciutto and provolone.ribblets: pork ribs in a house blend of seasonings.the peppers were an interesting taste, served cold in olive oil, it was a bite that burst with flavor. &nbsp;the ribblets were also quite tasty, when they were served on the bone, i initially thought &quot;oh, no....&quot; but the meat just fell off, it was tender and nothing you had to fight with or create a mess out of. &nbsp; also a food truck is parked outside that belongs to the bar, so if you got food from it you were more than welcome to bring it inside.such an adorable place, amazing staff (!!) i can't wait to have another date night here!
love this place, it's a total gem. came here last weekend before hunger games yeaaaa at la live. bf and i got here and it was amazing how incredibly shady/ghetto the entire area was but there was just one street, industrial street that was nicer. we got really lucky and parked right outside their door. thank god for my car! cuz honestly very few cars could fit in that space. anyways, parked for free very easily, and walked in. it was pretty empty but it was only 7. (we missed <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> by 2 minutes, sad) we walked in and were greeted by a delicious splash of spanish bubbly and truffle popcorn. honestly though it was a nice gesture, the popcorn was a little stale and not crunchy anymore. (half star off)bf ordered a glass of the spanish bubbly and i ordered a flight of australia for a specific riesling. it was all sooo delicious and great. we ordered all three of the snack plates. one was delicious ribs with the perfect amount of sauce, the second a plate of teeny tiny peppers (cherry tomato sized) stuffed with cheeses in olive oil. the last was stuffed mushrooms which was definitely my favorite. the peppers came second as i normally don't eat any kind of pepper but this was not so spicy/peppery and only packed a tiny bit of heat towards the end. i would recommend all three items though but if you can only get one, cheese stuffed peppers might be a good idea, more unique. anyways the wine flight was just delightful, the pours were generous. the lights were dim and perfect for winding down (especially after suffering from tension migraines for days from stress at job) they have board games and bottles of wine for sale, priced reasonably. service was also great and our server very friendly, but i took half a star off for letting my glass be empty for too long. i finished off my first pour but had to wait a bit until i made eye contact and flagged him down to get my second pour. next time, i plan on going when i'm not in such a time crunch, wear comfy clothes, order a bottle and sit down to beat my bf's ass in board games.
pour haus is a fun place in dtla. as soon as you enter, you're greeted with a complimentary tasting of wine. i'm not a big wine drinker, but the house sweet wine of the night was delicious. i forgot to ask what it was, but i was pretty set on having beer for the night anyways.their beer selection is awesome. they have a huge chalkboard wall full of choices that will satisfy even the pickiest of drinkers. not sure, ask your waiter, they can give you the 411 on everything offered and what they taste like.for food, i had one of jerome w's oxtail tacos. they came in a serving of five and had a good amount of spice to them. the bruschetta was pretty amazing with the bread being nice and toasted served with a big pile of tomato and garlic goodness on top. on the menu it warns you that they are generous with the garlic - and they aren't kidding around. my breath was probably kicking after that bite.for my own eats, i got an americano sandwich that had short rib and a horseradish cream sauce. it was well worth the price and they didn't skimp on the meat. i'm not usually a fan of horseradish, and it wasn't too overpowering and i actually enjoyed it. the best way to describe this would be that it's like a great grilled cheese with meat that has a spicy kick to it. i'd order it again.service was great. the guy taking care of us was attentive and always asking if we needed anything else and clearing glasses/plates almost immediate after they were emptied. even with a big group, everything went smoothly!parking is sorta difficult. if you get there early enough, you can find parking nearby, otherwise be prepared to take a little hike through some not so fun parts of the neighborhood. it's pretty close to tent city, so there are a lot of homeless people, which is fine, but you'll probably get asked for money every five feet.there is a valet parking lot across the street for $8... i was being cheap and didn't want to pay. be careful with the $5 valet that's nearby, it closes at 10pm. luckily the man was nice enough to let me know and that i should park my car elsewhere.all and all, i had a great time and would definitely come back and recommend to friends that were looking for a nice spot in dtla! they have a great <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> during the week and can accommodate large parties of people, just call ahead and let them know you're coming!
