darling newish bar that feels equally downtown and french quarter. big tacky drapes, oil portraits and chandelieeeeers. nice and spacious when you walk in, and a labyrinthine corridor leads to a courtyard with a gurgling fountain. they have live jazz three days a week, more like a diversion than bona fide entertainment, but no cover, and it's good. so is the food. the blackened catfish tacos were amazing, the best fish tacos i've ever had. red beans and rice were good, but i was hoping for classic dirty rice like zatarain's. these were more spanish style with a brisket based sauce. debris fries were like waffle fries poutine, the closest thing to the real thing i've had outside of canada, with yummy pan drippings. cocktails are about like what you'd have on bourbon street. i got a sazerac, not a hurricane. p&amp;p wins for frozen drinks, outdoor seating and a late night food <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, but little easy is more fun to get drunk in and has better food and service. i love kat the bartender, who also works at the love song bar.
osso-dtla-los-angeles
enjoyed: interesting space, great menu, awesome fried chicken, beaverdusa punchmeh: empty, saying there's a &quot;<span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>&quot; is misleading, incredibly low lightinghit up this spot on a thursday after work hoping to catch their <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, but soon found out that there really isn't such a thing. no drink specials and i was promptly informed that the kitchen doesn't open till 6. if you checked out osso's website and saw their &quot;<span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> 5-6pm tues-fri&quot; just know that that's a lie.i do have to say that i very much enjoyed the cocktails i sampled, which was the east 180 and beaverdusa punch. between the two, i lean towards the herbal-strong beaverdusa.in regards to food, my party ordered:* beef biltong: good, but made me want the real thing.* onion rings: decent and came with a sesame dipping sauce.* foie gras torchon: decent. osso's jam was a nice addition.* wax beans: very much enjoyed this dish, though the served portion could have been larger.* hamachi crudo: personally, i felt like this dish was over-complicated and neither the pho broth or basil made any noticeable impact on the taste profile.* fried chicken: awesome. this was actually a surprise, but that may have been due to my open expectations. nicely seasoned breading and incredibly juicy meat.beyond the food and drink, i was incredibly surprised that my party was one of just two groups in osso the whole night. i think that their food definitely deserves stronger patronage, but maybe it's their location or that they're new? if you're considering to check them out, i'd recommend satiating your curiosity with a visit.
osso, a vulgar latin word for bone. perhaps this place wanted to be a rib joint. oso, is spanish for bear, which could be a typo as the place is truly bare. the menu on flimsy paper has an image of a rat sired by a beaver and sprouting snakes from its head. what does it all mean? oh, so who cares? this spot is located in the warehouse district which is seedier than a bird feeder. park in back and maybe no one from the third world medical center will belly ache after 5:00 pm. two <span class="highlighted">hour</span> parking on the street and hope they leave the fancy lug nuts from your beemer. is this a bar with snacks? well, yes. is it a serious restaurant with a small cocktail program. yes, that too. the place kinda doesn't know what it wants to be as if chaz bono came up with the concept. the interior is your basic industrial shabby chic and has all the atmosphere of the last scene in a &quot;b&quot; crime thriller where the former alcoholic detective does mortal combat with the serial killer russian drug lord. you know the look, concrete floors, plaster missing to reveal the former incarnation. you have entered the world of noir dining. the place is large and opens onto the street with a commanding view of the roadway overpass and prime seats for the sharks rumble with the jets over turf. of the four snacks they were 86 on two of them. i was resigned to a bowl of house made salt and vinegar chips. they got hoovered before the drinks appeared. no matter, just order more. the hola chingo was cimarron tequila blanco, lime, blueberry cordial (very aussie, or make that very osso-ey), and bubbly wine all in a frosty tall glass. i'll have two and someone please hail the uber driver.there are seven listed &quot;cocktamologist&quot; signature concoctions, a small list of craft beers, and a minuscule wine list. no worries , you'll find something interesting. the menu too, is small but the kitchen is all business and very serious about what they are sending out. the chilled wax beans with dill kefir, candied almonds, and smoked cured yolk was unusual &nbsp; and unusually good. tart, refreshing and as summery as the perfect picnic. after that, the eatin' got down to real business. the patty melt would have made john montagu, the 4th earl of sandwich, smile so wide his whiskered lips would've been touchin' his ear lobes. house baked rye bread, thick juicy beef patty, caramelized onions, cheddar and swiss and served so hot and melting it needed oven mitts to hold it.next came the fried chicken. brined, buttermilked (probably), and fried so crisp, biting into a that moist breast might crack all those crowns you're still making payments on. is this the best fried chicken in the city right now? yes, no question. (sorry ludo.) all the competitors will just lay an egg next to this version. worth every nickel of the $35 for a whole bird. dessert? bring cookies from home. maybe this place opened up for the staff to enjoy, and they do and if you like it too, that's a plus. the servers aren't professional but they are willing, genuinely outgoing, welcoming and <span class="highlighted">happy</span> to please. you want full service, a somm, a large menu close by? hoof the 7 blocks to bestia and beg. you want strait ahead, down home, no foolin' really good grub, you've arrived. note to self: 20% is automatically added, so ave your change for the parking meters. the note is prominent on the menu and they tell you up front. take a lesson maude...which which requires a jewelers loop to read the fine print. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; funky neighborhood, small limited menu? no matter, osso, is oh so good.
