ld definitely come back to try other things on their menu!
wow. what an incredible meal we just had tonight. there aren't too many restaurants i have been this impressed with in a while. from their fresh seafood to amazing grilled meats, everything was prepared to perfection! &nbsp;since they offer a fully stocked raw-bar with a wide variety of ceviche we decided on sampling their peruvian ceviche (basically salmon crudo topped with a sweet/savory salsa) served with a side of popcorn. it was nice and refreshing, though a tad bit sweet. i personally prefer my raw seafoods a little on the simpler side, just dressed with lemon/lime and a pinch of salt, nothing more. also ordered a half dozen oysters served with fresh grated horseradish, mignonette sauce and tapatio. wish they offered spicy cocktail sauce and tabasco for those oysters instead of tapatio. during <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> (daily from 3-7pm) oysters go for $1 a pop! such a steal!! we followed our raw seafood appetizers with fried fish this time opting to try the baja beer battered cod fish tacos w/aji, crema, slaw &amp; salsa. one of the best fish tacos i've had. perfect crisp battered cod. for entree i opted for their grilled lamb special of the night served w/garlic rice and a choice of side. went with the brussels sprouts w/bacon. to die for! haden't had lamb taste so delicate like this before, grilled to absolute perfection, melt in your mouth tender. those brussels sprouts w/bacon were also quite amazing. they were topped with some sort of insanely delicious sauce i wanted to drink up with a straw.fire grilled churrasco ribeye steak w/chimichurri was served w/garlic rice and choice of side. another incredible perfectly grilled protein of the night. honestly, i highly recommend ordering their meats vs. ceviche. it's that mind blowing good. don't get me wrong, the ceviche is also quite tasty, but their meats were far more superior. let's not forget to mention the best mac n' cheese of all time! made with organic cinghiale pasta, bechamel, cali-cow cheddar cheese, goat cheese, panko bread crumbs, bacon. i was lost for words. ended our meal with dessert, the cerveteca sundae - fried ice cream with fried plantains. felt somewhat like a churro ice cream sandwich. pretty tasty way to seal the deal.there wasn't much we could nit pick to complain about. highly recommend stopping by for an unforgettable meal, and highly recommend ordering their grilled meats as they were executed to perfection! location wise they are in the heart of the art's district, a bit hard to find. spot 'eat drink americano' and you'll find them in the same complex a few doors down. they've occupied the former r23 sushi joint.
cerveteca should settle in nicely into the neighborhood once it gets its sea legs.located next door to another neighborhood favorite of mine, eat drink americano, cerveteca shows promise. &nbsp;the interior is simply laid out and has a mix of raised seating areas and standard tables. &nbsp;the red brick walls lend an industrial feel to the space. &nbsp;the music is at volume where you can hear the other party talk to you, but you will have to speak in elevated voices throughout the evening. &nbsp;in other words, a great place to hang out with friends, but maybe not the best for an intimate date.the menu has a good mix of mexican inspired entrees and appetizers with a ceviche raw bar for good measure. &nbsp;we ordered the yellowtail ceviche, which was just ok. &nbsp;there was too much ponzu or soy sauce seasoning and the yellowtail wasn't in small chunks, but rather large strips. &nbsp;i ordered the grilled salmon tacos, which come two to an order. &nbsp;overall, a solid dish with lots of shredded cabbage and toppings. &nbsp;these are a good size and will fill you up just enough without feeling too full. &nbsp;the organic chicken enchilada with tomatillo sauce was a bit of a disappointment. &nbsp;first off, the dish was very lukewarm in temperature when it first arrived. &nbsp;second, it's just two enchiladas with white rice on the side. &nbsp;it seemed like a bit of a letdown. &nbsp;when a manager came by to ask how we were doing and we noted the enchilada dish he was apologetic and kindly comped the dish even though we were fine with paying for it.cerveteca has a <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> from 3-7pm and seems like a perfect place to come for drinks and appetizers or a light dinner. &nbsp;there are enough tv screens to watch sporting events, but are not too intrusive to make it feel like a sports bar by any means. &nbsp;the manager/staff obviously seem to care about the food and overall dining experience so my kudos to them. &nbsp;cerveteca is still experiencing growing pains, but with a little more time could be a great spot.
3 1/2 starscame here for dinner with a friend. it's a big hard to find at first, but it's right next to eat drink americano. there is some street parking, but luckily we took an uber. the inside itself is real nice, i would say industriel chic. a bit cozy, dim and romantic. they have a pretty good selection to choose from the menu. from raw bar, burgers, tacos and main dishes. i would say a bit mexican food mixed with peruvian._red sangria ($10) this was good. nicely sweet, and not too strong or bitter it was the perfect sangria to start the night. i would get this again! _baja fish tacos ($5) (1 each)beer battered cod, aji, creme, slaw, salsa. this was pretty good. the fish was nicely battered, lots of slaw and good amount of creme and salsa. it was good but i think it's pretty pricey for 1. i've had many fish tacos that were just as good, even better for half the price! _tacos de barbacoa ($5) (1 each) braised shredded beef, guajillo, cilantro, red onions, mama's salasa. this was just okay. the beef was juicy and a tad spicy. we did eat the tortilla, because we did not want to get too full before our entrees, but to me this was just soso. and for $5 it was not worth it. the tortilla is warm and soft._herb basted game hen ($21) achiote, thyme, rosemary with arroz ajillo, choice of side, bread or tortillas. nice presentation, pretty big entree for one person. i'd say 2 can share this as well. the hen was cooked perfectly. nicely grilled and juicy. the marinade was a bit citrus like and a tad sweet. the rice was so fluffy and tasty! the bread that came with it was nicely grilled and crisp but the taste was a bit like burnt gas. the red salsa on the side was great! not too spicy but the right amount of taste to go with the hen and even drizzle on the rice. for my side, i got the maple brussel sprouts w/smoked bacon. this was so good. if you don't like your veggies, then try this because you just may change your mind. the brussels were cooked perfecly, the maple sauce was sweet and thick and with the thick bacon bits, you get sweet and salty. _churrasco ribeye steak ($28) fire grilled, chimichurri, served with arroz ajillo, choice of side, bread or tortillas. so initially my friend ordered their special of the day, which was the lamb chop but they were all out so we got ribeye instead. this too came out huge. the ribeye was cooked perfectly medium rare, however the taste was off. i don't know if it's the marinade but my friend was not liking it. he said it tasted like gas. i took a bite and knew what he meant. we asked our waitress if it was made over a gas and not grill but she said no. what ever the case it had a bad aftertaste and he is one to never bring back the food but it was to the point where he just was not enjoying it. our waitress was nice to take it back and exchange for another dish. we got there other special of the day, which was the branzino._branzino special of the day. i'm used to having branzino already served fillet style, without any of the bones, but this came as the whole fish, which was nince but a huge hassle to eat as there were bones everywhere. the taste was good, branzino tends to be a bit bland but so good to pair with sides that have lots of flavor. overall i don't think i would come here again, ,unless a friend wanted to come or it's a birthday. the tacos were overpriced, and the entrees tasted a bit like burnt gas for some reason. maybe it was just us but i think i expected too much from the reviews. i would maybe come check out their <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> menu since i did enjoy the red sangria. service was good.
cerveteca is a super hip and absolutely delicious latin joint in dtla's arts district. &nbsp;great food, stellar service, nice ambience...this is a must try!=food= &nbsp; &nbsp;1) chinese chicken kale salad - don't ask why i had this at a latin restaurant, but i'm actually glad i did! &nbsp;kale, cabbage, carrots, green onion, mandarin oranges, toasted sesame, onions, cilantro and chicken. &nbsp;yum! &nbsp;the chicken could've been a little more tender, but it was good regardless, and i'd get this dish again! &nbsp; &nbsp;2) tacos de barbacoa - it comes with 2 tacos of braised shredded beef on house made corn masa tortillas, guajillo, cilantro, red onion, and salsa. &nbsp;i didn't get to try the entire thing, but i was able to get a taste of the braised shredded beef. &nbsp;it was so delicious, juicy and tender. &nbsp;i was actually kind of bummed i didn't order my own. &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;3) half a dozen oysters - delicious and fresh! &nbsp;they have cholula, horse radish, lime, and red wine vinaigrette. &nbsp;the oysters that they had were from mexico and a bit more firm than others, but still......so good. &nbsp;i can eat oysters for days. &nbsp;it's such a shame that i didn't get this for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>...only $1/oyster! &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;4) cerveteca sundae - yum! &nbsp;fried ice-cream and plantains. &nbsp;there's also strawberries on the side! &nbsp;i love that the ice-cream and the plantains balanced out each other in terms of sweetness (you wouldn't think so, right?)! &nbsp;  &nbsp; &nbsp;5) organic chicken enchiladas with mole - very good! &nbsp;i really like mole and haven't had mole in so long that the semi-chocolaty sauce was perfect to me. &nbsp;just the right amount of savory with the hint of that chocolate. &nbsp;it's definitely not for all, but it was definitely for me!=service=i've been here twice and the service was spot on each time. &nbsp;everyone here is very friendly and helpful. &nbsp;i've had waiters sit down next to you to have small conversations with you as well. &nbsp;food came out in good timing, and we were always being checked on to make see if things were to our liking. &nbsp;we even stayed past their closing once, they were still so kind to us! =location/parking &amp; ambience=the only thing about this place that i'm not used to is the lighting. &nbsp;it's very dim, so in the evening, it's quite dark inside. &nbsp;perfect little place to catch up with a few friends and grab food and drinks, or even for a nice date! &nbsp;it's located in a little alley next to eat drink americano, and so close to wurstkuche. &nbsp;there's parking all along the streets and about 2 or 3 spots right in front of the restaurant in the alley. &nbsp;if you come during prime eating <span class="highlighted">hours</span>, you'll find it harder to locate a spot, but it's definitely not impossible...and everything's within parking distance.=final verdict=they have great service and delicious food! &nbsp;i love this place and will be a repeat customer again and again!
i went to <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> today for the first time and was very disappointed with the service. &nbsp;it began with our arrival around 5:30 we were seated promptly and our drink orders were taken. &nbsp;we received our drinks in about 10 minutes and placed our orders of 10 oysters, a taco, and wings around 5:40. &nbsp;other parties began to arrive and placed orders for drinks and food. &nbsp;one particular &nbsp;party sitting across from our table received drinks and food within 15 minutes. i also noticed the same table was conversing &nbsp;with other wait staff and giving each other a high five before there food quickly came out. 5:40 turned to 6:15 then 6:25 finally i asked our waiter if she could check our order. &nbsp;the manager then came to our table and apologized for the service and said an incident occurred in the kitchen and we'd be getting our food soon. &nbsp;we received &nbsp;a 3rd of our order at 6:35 then another item came at 6:40. we finally received what i'd consider the easiest item to prepare, the oysters, around 6:50 and water was also finally brought. &nbsp;the food was decent but the owners should strongly consider examining the efficiency of it's staff. &nbsp;i also noticed the manager texting on her phone during our service. i hope this review helps the owners and other customers because the place has potential but with bad service like this can ruin an establishment.
loved this place! i'll summarize first and then i'll go into the details. food: super tasty and down-right delicious. no fancy concoctions of various animal parts mixed with french techniques and this and that. straight up food made like grandma made it if grandma had a cool, hipster-type sous chef! ambiance and service: cozy, super chill, but without taking itself too seriously; only dedicated to making your experience absolutely delightful, which they did!went with the family after watching a show at the wd concert hall. after a search on yelp (of course!) i realized that most places didn't open for dinner until after 6, when all the cool, non-family types apparently go out to eat. since i clearly don't fall into that camp, i chose cerveteca because it was open earlier than that. as we walked in, they immediately noticed my little ones and pointed out that they had reserved a table with bar stools for us, but we could choose to sit on the lower tables if that would be more comfortable for the kids. we moved to a table with short chairs right in front of a large open window with the most incredible view of what's happening in dtla right now: in the forefront a fence with barbed wire and walls filled with murals and graffiti, in the background the la skyscrapers. our server was super friendly! it's always tricky when trying new, off-the-beaten path places with kids because you're not sure how &quot;kid friendly&quot; the place or the service will be. and by kid friendly i don't mean that i expect the menu to have chicken fingers (yuck!), but that the service will be welcoming and most of all, accommodating. welcoming and accommodating these folks were! my son asked for chocolate milk and our server paused and told him he didn't think they had any, but that he would go back and see if they could create something. my son was <span class="highlighted">happy</span> and satisfied and although they couldn't whip up the chocolate milk, he did bring him mint lemonade and when my son's face shriveled upon tasting it (it was a bit sour and tart for a 6 year old), our server took it back and added some simple syrup to make it sweeter. how awesome is that?!!ok what we ordered: pulled pork with papas bravas tator tots for my 11 year old who couldn't stop licking her fingers and stuffing her face. the pork was juicy, marinated in spices, and then the sauce kicked it all up to another level! the tator tots were like little pillows of heaven (yes i tasted everyone's food!). my 6 year old had the mac n cheese which were oven baked sea shells that tasted like the mexican version of &quot;sopita&quot;: pasta lightly pan fried with onions, garlic and tomato sauce and then cooked in chicken broth. it had manchego (i think. it was a tasty melting cheese) and goat cheese melted over it with a light crunch. amazing! the husband had the chorizo burger: it had chorizo. enough said. i had the chicken enchiladas in mole sauce with a side of plantains. the mole..........it's so hard to make good mole, to make it &quot;just right.&quot; the only other place outside my mother's kitchen that makes excellent mole is &quot;la casita mexicana&quot; in bell and now cerveteca. it was the perfect blend of sweet, smoky, cocoa-ey and with a kick. the chicken was juicy, tender, tasty. i used the plantains to &quot;lick&quot; off any trace of mole left on the plate - it was that good!no dessert, although we really wanted to! we just couldn't possibly stuff any more food into our faces. because we got there at 5, our drinks were priced at <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> prices which was awe-some! can't wait to come back!!
