this is a good looking place right on the edge of a questionable neighborhood. they have a good amount of outdoor seating including a portion of the bar.we came by for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. we tried a few of their options. the jalape&ntilde;o hush puppies were solid. you get a decent number and the honey butter adds a nice accent. the sharp cheddar gooey mac &amp; cheese is also fairly good. you get a good sized bowl. it is gooey and has good flavor. the goldfish crumble topping is a nice touch too. the last thing we tried was the drew's bomb brisket chili. the chili tasted pretty darn good. i just wish there was a little less hominy in it. they pack in a good amount of brisket, but it was lost on me because of all the hominy. i do not dislike hominy, i just do not want it to dominate the dish from a texture perspective.overall this is a cool place to meet for drinks and appetizers. i would just feel better about it if it was a few blocks further west. i realize that is not what people want to hear, but it is reality.
i love going to wine bars where the employees know their stuff but aren't super pretentious about wines. like, don't serve me box wine but i'm not paying $80 for a glass of beaujolais because the grapes were crushed by toddlers in the south of france. after going to the california science center to see the dead sea scrolls i had a hankering for some good wine. the bf found this place which is located down the most random alley in the fashion district. like, as we drove through the fashion district i was trying to think of wine bars but i could only think of random hot dog or falafel carts. when we parked in some random parking lot and walked over i could start to tell how cool the must is. first of all, the music was on point. there were some people that just had to jump up and start dancing and i couldn't even blame them.we sat at the bar and were immediately served. since it was <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> we worked from that menu. we ordered olives, latkes, and a cheese board. oh, and a couple glasses of wine, of course. we also looked at the cocktail menu and the cocktails looked good. i hate when i'm conflicted. like when i go somewhere looking for wine and then the cocktails look bomb. ugh. first world problems. anyway, the latkes were something special. nicely deep fried and a little salty. l'chaim! the service was awesome and for our second glass the bartender recommended a chilled red that was outstanding. i really liked this place. i just love unstuffy wine bars.
after getting a drink at perch my friends and i wanted some inexpensive food so we walked over to the must. it's in a strange area, where you wouldn't expect to see such a trendy bar. the atmosphere is awesome. interior brick, large patio, high ceilings. we went during <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> (3-7 daily) on a saturday and there was like no one there which was great! we ordered the french fries ($4), chicken wings ($5), flying dog ipa ($8), and two glasses of the house white wine ($5). the fries were so good, and topped with parmesan. two orders were definitely enough for four people. the boyfriends loved the wings as well. i was skeptical about the house white wine but it turned out to be very refreshing and not too sweet. my only reason for the three stars is the service. our server (who i think was named lauren), was very nice and pleasant at the beginning. when we first sat down she came and took our order quick, and we received our drinks and food relatively fast. but then she kind of disappeared. we got there around 3:30 and didn't leave until about 4:45, and we didn't even order that much. we were on a time constraint and since there weren't that many people at the restaurant there was really no excuse for her to take so long to come check on us. she was a very nice girl though! i'll probably give it another try someday!
we came down to downtown for a concert and were looking for a good place to eat beforehand. the must was a perfect place to stop for early night noshing! <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> on saturday: awesome! service: incredibly helpful and nice! (the waitress was appropriately funny/snarky in her banter throughout the entire meal) drink selection: many great wine and beer choices with a full bar that we didn't try (the bier milano doppio malto was very yummy!). food: all very good! (the smashed tater tots are a must!) desserts: all looked super good, and we got to enjoy a very good birthday ice cream cake (for free!!! bro-in-laws bday!) and atmosphere: very cool, clean, modern, and warm as well. we would definitely come back!
