what a fun place--just steps from skid row in hipster la. the restaurant is on a small street in la, with plenty of street or lot parking nearby. the block slopes downhill toward los angeles street, so the restaurant is slightly elevated from street level with a bar and interior seating. but the patio is the bomb! we sat outside enjoying the early evening breeze and views of street art on the walls across the street. they have a nice <span class="highlighted">happy</span> menu of drinks and snacks. we indulged in the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> drinks, but hit the regular menu for its unique and tasty morsels. our group of four shared the smashed tots and chimichurri cauliflower, both delicious and unusual. the restaurant has a small, but eclectic group of larger plates as well, which are vegan and omnivore- friendly. my veg friend couldn't resist ordering the beet loaf, which was made of red beets and quinoa, sitting in a delicious pool of mashed potatoes. my wife had the green bucatini, which was a think spaghetti-like pasta covered in a pesto and enhanced by salty, delicious sea beens. my other friend and i both had the sockeye salmon, which was served in a broth of manila clams and accompanied by a toasted piece of french bread and those tasty sea beans as well. be sure to ask your server for a spoon to sop up the broth. unfortunately, we were too full to sample the fluffernutter pie, which brings you right back to your childhood. much better than vegemite i might add. nicole, our server, was just the right amount of fun. there are plenty of good restaurants on the block from blossom to baco mercat, but you ought to, you should, heck you must try the must.
