it is a crime against humanity that i have never written a review about this unique dtla bar. &nbsp;the edison has been a beautiful backdrop to many wonderful dtla outings with friends et. al. &nbsp;although it was not a part of minty's dtla dive bar crawl last friday (how could it be? &nbsp;it is not divey at all! &nbsp;it's gorgeous), it was my first stop and meeting place with anthony. &nbsp;as a restored basement of the southern california edison power plant with incredible, low-lit, cool, jazz-playing ambiance, you'll take a trip back to the roaring 1920's, flappers, classic bartenders, beautiful woodwork, with good drinks and food. &nbsp;they used to have these <span class="highlighted">happy hours</span> for .35 cocktails and free grill cheese with tomato soup. &nbsp;but long after that special stopped, they have a 40% off <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. the sliders are made to perfection, medium rare, watercress topped, juicy and delicious. &nbsp;the truffle mac and cheese is yummy. &nbsp;the drinks are made of unique flavors and served with class. i loved the mistress and the brass flower. &nbsp;the dress code also brings the crowd up to a nice level of class. &nbsp;they have dinner and dancing later in the evening. &nbsp;unfortunately, i was disappointed at the lack of crowd when i went last friday for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. &nbsp;meaning, people... why are you not supporting great classic <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> spots like the edison?!?!?! &nbsp;go and support these beautiful fantastic dtla venues! &nbsp;stop chasing the new! &nbsp;it's not as good. &nbsp;fortunately, later on our bar crawl when we left the redwood and , i noticed the business was booming at the edison, right down to the red rope and limos. &nbsp;yay! &nbsp;now just get your office mates out for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, people!
