l gotta check it out. i'm down for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> anytime.
come here for the <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>! you will not be disappointed. they have their special <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> serving $.35 aviators and $1 martinis every wednesday and thursday. they open at 5:00 pm for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, right in time to welcome the young professionals through the door.food: they have a menu with 5 items, each for $5. get anything with fries because their fries are delicious! the kobe beef slider is also really good too. each plate of food is the perfect portion to eat by yourself while not filling you up too much.service: right at 5:00 pm, there aren't too many people here yet so you get a lot of attention from your bartender who are very friendly and helpful. also, another perk for getting here on the early side is that you beat the crowd and assure yourself a nice and comfy seat at the bar. seating at the bar is key because seating at any of the open tables requires a minimum charge.decor: the interior of this place is amazingly gorgeous. inspired by the 1920s prohibition era, it gives off a vibe of secret and speak-easy bar. it's also very spacious inside, sure to be a great destination for any large party.tip: be sure to get a token from the hostess at the entrance. this token will give you access to the cheap drinks. i think you only get to choose one. the aviators are pretty good and surprisingly strong. i think i remember the martinis from my last visit weren't that great, but i'm not really a martini girl anyway.
i was hesitant at first when i heard about this place being an old powerplant. &nbsp;&quot;am i going to deteriorate from the radiation?&quot; or &quot;is my skin going to change colors?&quot;. &nbsp;i know i'm just exaggerating and they wouldn't open a prestige place like this for the public to hang out and have some c&amp;c (company and conversation).the 1920's ambiance is very unique. &nbsp;it has that gothic/vintage atmosphere when you enter from the spiral staircase. &nbsp;me and the wifey came here during <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> from 5pm-7pm on a weeknight. &nbsp;it was the best time after work and have a drink or two chilling in a old fashionable sofa. &nbsp;when i was kinda buzzed, i would trip out from watching the silent movies they were showing in tv. they serve different kinds of beer poured in a big glass and mixed drinks. &nbsp;on weeknights at <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>, you get a free token for a free martini. i love that. self parking is plenty coming from the entrance at main st. and i paid $5. &nbsp;i had fun hanging out having my glass of stella artois.
with 1099 reviews, the edison probably doesn't need one more from me, but oh well.advice on how to best enjoy it if you're not looking to spend a lot:1. have fun with the dress code. don't get stressed out and start talking about &quot;guh so la&quot; ... just treat it as a fun excuse to dress up;2. go for <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span>. at 5-5:30, the edison is empty. you can sit anywhere, explore the whole bar, and avoid some of the more intense patrons. also! <span class="highlighted">happy hour</span> features drink tickets for a $1 cocktail... the cocktail changes (i think daily), but they make their drinks well. i've never had anything that wasn't at least decent, and for $1 plus that setting, who can complain?3. don't valet (if you're being cost conscious, at least). there's tons of cheaper parking available downtown;4. get your $1 cocktail, wander around a little, use the fancy bathrooms, and then move on. all of a sudden, the edison is the cheapest bar experience in la. there are a lot of great bars downtown to move onto.
